{{flagicon image|Flag of Taliban.svg}} '''Taliban'''\n| {{flagicon image|Flag of Taliban.svg|size=23px}} '''[[Mohammed Omar]]'''<br /><small>(1st Supreme Commander of the Taliban)</small>(2001-2013)<br />{{flagicon image|Flag of Taliban.svg|size=23px}} '''[[Akhtar Mansour]]'''{{KIA}}<br /><small>(2nd Supreme Commander of the Taliban)</small><br />{{flagicon image|Flag of Taliban.svg|size=23px}} '''[[Hibatullah Akhundzada]]'''<br /><small>(Current & 3rd Supreme Commander of the Taliban)</small><br />{{flagicon image|Flag of Taliban.svg|size=23px}} [[Quetta Shura]]<br /><small>(Senior Taliban council)</small>{{flagicon image|Flag of Taliban.svg|size=23px}} [[Abdul Ghani Baradar]]<br />{{flagicon image|Flag of Taliban.svg|size=23px}} [[Obaidullah Akhund]]{{KIA}}<br />{{flagicon image|Flag of Taliban.svg|size=23px}} [[Mohammad Fazl]]<br />{{flagicon image|Flag of Taliban.svg|size=23px}} [[Dadullah Akhund]]{{KIA}}\n}}\n{{collapsible list\n| bullets = no\n| title ={{flagicon image|Flag of Tehrik-i-Taliban.svg}} '''Tehrik-i-Taliban'''\n| {{flagicon image|Flag of Tehrik-i-Taliban.svg|size=23px}} '''[[Maulana Fazlullah]]'''<br /><small>(Emir of Tehrik-i-Taliban Pakistan)</small>\n}}\n{{collapsible list\n| bullets = no\n| title ='''Haqqani Network'''\n| {{flagicon image|Flag of Jihad.svg}} '''[[Jalaluddin Haqqani]]'''{{KIA}}<br /><small>(leader of the Haqqani network)</small><br />\n| {{flagicon image|Flag of Jihad.svg}} [[Sirajuddin Haqqani]]\n}}\n{{collapsible list\n| bullets = no\n| title ={{flagicon image|Flag of Turkistan Islamic Party.svg}} '''East Turkestan Islamic Movement'''\n| {{flagicon image|Flag of Turkistan Islamic Party.svg|22px}} '''[[Abdul Haq (ETIP)|Abdul Haq]]'''<br /><small>{{KIA}}(Emir of the East Turkestan Islamic Movement)</small><br />{{flagicon image|Flag of Turkistan Islamic Party.svg|22px}} '''[[Abdullah Mansour]]'''<br /><small>(Emir of the East Turkestan Islamic Movement)</small>\n}}\n}}\n\nThe '''War on Terror''', also known as the '''Global War on Terrorism''', is an international military campaign launched by the [[Federal government of the United States|United States government]] after the [[September 11 attacks]].<ref name=\"Schmitt/slogan\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/07/26/politics/26strategy.html?_r=0 |title=U.S. Officials Retool Slogan for Terror War|newspaper=New York Times|date=26 July 2005|author=Eric Schmitt|author2=Thom Shanker}}</ref> The targets of the campaign are primarily [[Sunni Islam|Sunni]] [[Islamism|Islamist]] [[Islamic fundamentalism|fundamentalist]] armed groups located throughout the [[Muslim world]], with the most prominent groups being [[Al-Qaeda]], the [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant|Islamic State]], the [[Taliban]], [[Tehrik-i-Taliban Pakistan]], and the various franchise groups of the former two organizations. The naming of the campaign uses a [[War as metaphor|metaphor of war]] to refer to a variety of actions that do not constitute a specific war as traditionally defined. U.S. president [[George W. Bush]] first used the [[Slogans and terms derived from the September 11 attacks|term]] \"war on terrorism\" on 16 September 2001,<ref name=\"evilwar\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://georgewbush-whitehouse.archives.gov/news/releases/2001/09/20010916-2.html|title=President: Today We Mourned, Tomorrow We Work|website=georgewbush-whitehouse.archives.gov|access-date=2019-11-26}}</ref> and then \"war on terror\" a few days later in a formal speech to Congress.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://georgewbush-whitehouse.archives.gov/news/releases/2001/09/20010920-8.html|title=President Declares \"Freedom at War with Fear\"|website=georgewbush-whitehouse.archives.gov|access-date=2019-11-26}}</ref><ref name=\"cnntranscript\" /> In the latter speech, George Bush stated, \"Our enemy is a radical network of terrorists and every government that supports them.\"<ref name=\"cnntranscript\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/nation/specials/attacked/transcripts/bushaddress_092001.html|title=Text: President Bush Addresses the Nation|date=20 September 2001|website=The Washington Post}}</ref> The term was originally used with a particular focus on countries associated with [[al-Qaeda]]. The term was immediately criticised by such people as [[Richard B. Myers]], chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, and more nuanced terms subsequently came to be used by the [[Presidency of George W. Bush|Bush administration]] to publicly define the international campaign led by the U.S.<ref name=\"Schmitt/slogan\" /> It was never used as a formal designation of U.S. operations in internal government documentation.<ref name=\"Ambinder2013\">{{cite news |title=The New Term for the War on Terror |author=Marc Ambinder |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2010/05/the-new-term-for-the-war-on-terror/56969/ |newspaper=The Atlantic |date=20 May 2010 |accessdate=24 June 2013}}</ref> There was a medal issued in the name of terrorism, however, the \"[[Global War on Terrorism Service Medal]]\".\n\nU.S. President [[Barack Obama]] announced on 23 May 2013 that the Global War on Terror was over, saying the military and intelligence agencies will not wage war against a tactic but will instead focus on a specific group of networks determined to destroy the U.S.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usnews.com/news/articles/2013/05/23/obama-global-war-on-terror-is-over|title=Obama: 'Global War on Terror' Is Over|work=U.S. News & World Report|date=23 May 2013}}</ref> On 28 December 2014, the Obama administration announced the end of the combat role of the U.S.-led mission in Afghanistan.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-afghanistan-war-idUSKBN0K60FB20141228|title=U.S.-led mission in Afghanistan ends combat role; thousands of troops remain|author=Kay Johnson|publisher=Reuters|date=28 December 2014}}</ref> However, the unexpected{{Citation needed|date=October 2019}} rise of the [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant]] (ISIL) terror group\u2014also known as the Islamic State of Iraq and Syria (ISIS)\u2014led to a new operation against terror in the Middle East and South Asia, [[Operation Inherent Resolve]].\n\n[[Criticism of the war on terror]] focused on morality, efficiency, and economics; some, including later president [[Barack Obama]],<ref>[http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2009/aug/06/white-house-war-terrorism-over/ White House: \u2018War on terrorism\u2019 is over] 6 August 2009.</ref><ref name=\"declover\" /><ref name=\"whitehdefuniv\" /><ref name=\"terrorover\" /> objected to the phrase itself as a [[misnomer]]. The notion of a \"war\" against \"terrorism\" has proven contentious, with critics charging that it has been exploited by participating governments to pursue long-standing policy/military objectives,<ref name=\"Monbiot2003\" /> reduce [[civil liberties]],<ref name=\"Wired-FBI\" /> and infringe upon human rights. Critics also assert that the term \"war\" is not appropriate in this context (much like the term \"[[War on Drugs]]\") since there is no identifiable enemy and it is unlikely that international terrorism can be brought to an end by military means.<ref name=\"Richissin\" />\n\n=={{anchor|Terminology}}Etymology==\nThe phrase \"War on Terror\" has been used to specifically refer to the ongoing military campaign led by the U.S., U.K. and their allies against organizations and regimes identified by them as terrorist, and usually excludes other independent [[counter-terrorism|counter-terrorist operations and campaigns]] such as those by Russia and India. The conflict has also been referred to by names other than the War on Terror. It has also been known as:\n* [[World War III]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/newsitems/200605/s1632213.htm|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110204112337/http://www.abc.net.au/news/newsitems/200605/s1632213.htm|archivedate=4 February 2011 |title=Bush likens 'war on terror' to WWIII|publisher=ABC News (Australia) |date=6 May 2006 |accessdate=26 March 2011}}<br />{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2001/09/13/opinion/foreign-affairs-world-war-iii.html?sec=&spon=&pagewanted=all |title=Foreign Affairs; World War III |author=Thomas L. Friedman |date=13 September 2009 |work=The New York Times |accessdate=10 November 2009}}<br />{{cite news |url=http://articles.nydailynews.com/2004-03-12/news/18257093_1_al-qaeda-mayor-bloomberg-basque |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121026154658/http://articles.nydailynews.com/2004-03-12/news/18257093_1_al-qaeda-mayor-bloomberg-basque |archivedate=26 October 2012 |title=World War II Strikes Spain |date=12 March 2004 |work=Daily News |location=New York |accessdate=10 November 2009 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n* World War IV<ref>{{cite news |title=Ex-CIA director: U.S. faces 'World War IV' |author1=Charles Feldman |author2=Stan Wilson |lastauthoramp=yes |publisher=CNN |date=3 April 2003 |url=http://www.cnn.com/2003/US/04/03/sprj.irq.woolsey.world.war/ |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080727025549/http://www.cnn.com/2003/US/04/03/sprj.irq.woolsey.world.war/index.html|archivedate=27 July 2008}}<br />{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/middleeast/syria/1427428/We-want-them-to-be-nervous-That-means-you-Ali-Bashar-and-Kim.html |title='We want them to be nervous' (That means you Ali, Bashar and Kim) |work=The Daily Telegraph |location=London |accessdate=9 November 2009 |first=Julian |last=Coman |date=13 April 2003}}<br />{{cite web |url=http://www.opinionjournal.com/editorial/feature.html?id=95001493 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040406043752/http://www.opinionjournal.com/editorial/feature.html?id=95001493 |archivedate=6 April 2004 |title=World War IV |author=Elio A. Cohen |date=20 November 2001 |website=The Wall Street Journal |accessdate=9 November 2009}}</ref> (assuming the [[Cold War]] was World War III)\n* Bush's War on Terror<ref>{{cite news|last=Thompson |first=Mark |url=http://www.time.com/time/nation/article/0,8599,1868367,00.html |title=The $1 Trillion Bill for Bush's War on Terror |work=TIME |date=26 December 2008 |accessdate=26 March 2011}}<br />{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2009/01/22/AR2009012203929.html |title=Bush's 'War' On Terror Comes to a Sudden End |work=The Washington Post |date=23 January 2009|accessdate=26 March 2011 |first=Dana |last=Priest}}<br />{{cite news|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2008/01/28/terror/main3757858.shtml |title=Bush's War On Terror Shifting Targets |publisher=CBS News |date=28 January 2008 |accessdate=26 March 2011}}</ref>\n* The Long War<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.heritage.org/Press/Commentary/ed090803a.cfm |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050909202409/http://www.heritage.org/Press/Commentary/ed090803a.cfm |archivedate=9 September 2005 |title=The Long War Against Terrorism |date=9 September 2005 |accessdate=2 January 2012}}<br />{{cite journal |last=Brownstein |first=Ronald |date=6 March 2015 |title=The Long War |url=http://www.nationaljournal.com/political-connections/the-long-war-20150306 |journal=National Journal |access-date=10 March 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"WaPo\">\"Abizaid Credited With Popularizing the Term 'Long War,'\" 3 February 2006: ''Washington Post'' traces history of the phrase \"Long War\" [https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2006/02/02/AR2006020202242.html]</ref>\n* The Forever War<ref>Elizabeth D. Samet, \"Literature of the Forever War\", ''[[The New York Times]]'', 14 August 2016, p. BR29.</ref>\n* The Global War on Terror<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.jfcom.mil/about/com_jfic.htm |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050204124824/http://www.jfcom.mil/about/com_jfic.htm |archivedate=4 February 2005 |title=Joint Forces Intelligence Command |date=4 February 2005 |accessdate=2 January 2012}}<br />{{cite web |url=http://8tharmy.korea.army.mil/35ada/dco.html |title=Eric L. Bradley, Deputy Commander |publisher=8tharmy.korea.army.mil |accessdate=2 January 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120327150252/http://8tharmy.korea.army.mil/35ada/dco.html |archivedate=27 March 2012}}<br />{{cite web |url=http://www.bisp.gov.pk/Default3.aspx |title=Compensation Package for Bomb Blast Victims |publisher=Bisp.gov.pk |date=1 January 1970 |accessdate=2 January 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111229063230/http://www.bisp.gov.pk/Default3.aspx |archivedate=29 December 2011}}</ref>\n* The War Against al-Qaeda<ref>{{cite web|last=Lucas |first=Fred |url=http://www.cnsnews.com/node/59446 |title=Obama Declares America 'At War' with Al Qaeda, Offers New Security Initiatives |publisher=CNSnews.com |date=7 January 2010 |accessdate=2 January 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111213153248/http://cnsnews.com/node/59446 |archivedate=13 December 2011}}<br />{{cite news|url=http://articles.sfgate.com/2007-02-20/opinion/17233057_1_al-qaeda-terror-promotion-of-human-rights |work=The San Francisco Chronicle |first=Glenn |last=Sulmasy |title=A new look for the war on al Qaeda |date=20 February 2007}}</ref>\n\n===History of use of the phrase and its rejection by the U.S. government===\nIn 1984, the [[Presidency of Ronald Reagan|Reagan administration]], which had significantly expanded the CIA-run [[Operation Cyclone|program of funding]] the mujaheddin militants in Afghanistan, employed the term \"war against terrorism\" to pass legislation aimed at countering terrorist groups in the wake of the [[1983 Beirut barracks bombing]] that killed 241 U.S. and 58 French [[peacekeeping|peacekeepers]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Silver |first=Alexandra |url=http://www.time.com/time/nation/article/0,8599,1973131,00.html |title=How America Became a Surveillance State |work=Time |date=18 March 2010 |accessdate=26 March 2011}}</ref> In 2017, [[U.S. Vice President]] [[Mike Pence]] called the 1983 Beirut barracks bombing \"the opening salvo in a war that we have waged ever since\u2014the global war on terror.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newsweek.com/trump-administration-says-war-terror-began-911-hezbollah-attack-us-troops-691653|title=Mike Pence says Hezbollah started the war on terror with a 1983 attack in Beirut|date=24 October 2017|work=Newsweek}}</ref>\n\nThe concept of the U.S. at war with terrorism may have begun on 11 September 2001 when [[Tom Brokaw]], having just witnessed the collapse of one of the towers of the [[World Trade Center (1973\u20132001)|World Trade Center]], declared \"Terrorists have declared war on [America].\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://archives.nbclearn.com/portal/site/k-12/flatview?cuecard=1419 |title=Breaking News on September 11th |author=Matt Lauer |author2=Katie Couric |author3=Tom Brokaw |date=11 September 2001 |website=NBC Learn K-12 |publisher=NBCUniversal Media |accessdate=11 September 2012|author2-link=Katie Couric |author-link=Matt Lauer}}</ref>\n\nOn 16 September 2001, at [[Camp David]], U.S. president George W. Bush used the phrase ''war on terrorism'' in an ostensibly unscripted comment when answering a journalist's question about the impact of enhanced law enforcement authority given to the [[Mass surveillance in the United States|U.S. surveillance]] agencies on Americans' civil liberties: \"This is a new kind of\u2014a new kind of evil.  And we understand.  And the American people are beginning to understand. This crusade, this war on terrorism is going to take a while.  And the American people must be patient.  I'm going to be patient.\"<ref name=\"evilwar\">{{cite news|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/archives/news/2001/09/17/2001-09-17_a_fight_vs__evil__bush_and_c.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100505200651/http://www.nydailynews.com/archives/news/2001/09/17/2001-09-17_a_fight_vs__evil__bush_and_c.html|archivedate=5 May 2010 |title=Kenneth R. Bazinet, \"A Fight Vs. Evil, Bush And Cabinet Tell U.S.\" |work=Daily News |location=New York |date=17 September 2001 |accessdate=26 March 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"evilwar2\">https://georgewbush-whitehouse.archives.gov/news/releases/2001/09/20010916-2.html Remarks by the President Upon Arrival The White House, 16 September 2001</ref> Shortly after, the White House said the president regretted use of the term ''crusade'', as it might have been misunderstood as referring to the historical [[Crusades]]; the word ''crusade'' was not used again.<ref>Jonathan Lyons, \"Bush enters Mideast's rhetorical minefield\" (Reuters: 21 September 2001). [http://hv.greenspun.com/bboard/q-and-a-fetch-msg.tcl?msg_id=006SM3 Greenspun.com]</ref> On 20 September 2001, during a televised address to a joint session of Congress, George Bush said, \"Our war on terror begins with al Qaeda, but it does not end there. It will not end until every terrorist group of global reach has been found, stopped and defeated.\"<ref name=whitehousejoint>[https://georgewbush-whitehouse.archives.gov/news/releases/2001/09/20010920-8.html Address to a Joint Session of Congress and the American People] The White House, 20 September 2001.</ref><ref name=cnntranscript>{{cite news|title=Transcript of President Bush's address |publisher=CNN |date=20 September 2001 |url=http://edition.cnn.com/2001/US/09/20/gen.bush.transcript/}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2007, the British government announced publicly that it was abandoning the use of the phrase \"war on terror\" as they found it to be less than helpful.<ref>{{cite news|last= Reynolds|first=Paul |date=17 April 2007 |title=Declining use of 'war on terror' |publisher=BBC |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/politics/6562709.stm}}</ref> This was explained more recently by Lady [[Eliza Manningham-Buller]]. In her 2011 [[Reith lecture]], the former head of [[MI5]] said that the 9/11 attacks were \"a crime, not an act of war. So I never felt it helpful to refer to a war on terror.\"<ref>{{cite news |last=Norton-Taylor |first=Richard |newspaper=The Guardian |date=2 September 2011 |title=MI5 former chief decries 'war on terror' |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2011/sep/02/mi5-war-on-terror-criticism |location=London}}</ref>\n\n[[File:OCO GWOT.jpg|thumb|Letter from Barack Obama indicating appropriation of Congressional funds for \"Overseas Contingency Operations/Global War on Terrorism\"]]\n\nU.S. president [[Barack Obama]] rarely used the term, but in his inaugural address on 20 January 2009, he stated: \"Our nation is at war, against a far-reaching network of violence and hatred.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/Inauguration/story?id=6689022&page=1 |title=FULL TRANSCRIPT: President Barack Obama's Inaugural Address|publisher=ABC News |date=20 January 2009 |accessdate=26 March 2011}}</ref> In March 2009 the Defense Department officially changed the name of operations from \"Global War on Terror\" to \"Overseas Contingency Operation\" (OCO).<ref name=\"oco-wapost\">{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2009/03/24/AR2009032402818.html|title='Global War On Terror' Is Given New Name|author1=Scott Wilson |author2=Al Kamen |lastauthoramp=yes |work=The Washington Post|date=25 March 2009 |page= A04|accessdate=14 September 2014}}</ref> In March 2009, the [[Presidency of Barack Obama|Obama administration]] requested that [[The Pentagon|Pentagon]] staff members avoid the use of the term and instead to use \"Overseas Contingency Operation\".<ref name=\"oco-wapost\"/> Basic objectives of the Bush administration \"war on terror\", such as targeting al Qaeda and building international counterterrorism alliances, remain in place.<ref>Jai Singh and Ajay Singh, \"[http://smallwarsjournal.com/printpdf/13142 The War on Terror \u2013 Over] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130120045914/http://smallwarsjournal.com/printpdf/13142 |date=20 January 2013}}?\", ''Small Wars Journal'', 28 August 2012.</ref><ref>David Kravets, \"[https://www.wired.com/threatlevel/2012/09/bush-obama-war-on-terror/ Former CIA Chief: Obama's War on Terror Same as Bush's, But With More Killing]\", ''Wired'', 10 September 2012.</ref>\n\nIn May 2010, the Obama administration published a report outlining its [[National Security Strategy (United States)|National Security Strategy]]. The document dropped the Bush-era phrase \"global war on terror\" and reference to \"Islamic extremism,\" and stated, \"This is not a global war against a tactic\u2014terrorism, or a religion\u2014Islam. We are at war with a specific network, al-Qaeda, and its terrorist affiliates who support efforts to attack the United States, our allies, and partners.\"<ref name=declover>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/barackobama/7772598/Barack-Obama-declares-the-War-on-Terror-is-over.html Barack Obama declares the 'War on Terror' is over: President Barack Obama has rejected George W. Bush's doctrine that placed the \"war on terror\" at the center of American foreign policy] ''The Telegraph'', 27 May 2010.</ref>\n\nIn December 2012, [[Jeh Johnson]], the [[General Counsel of the Department of Defense]], speaking at [[University of Oxford|Oxford University]], stated that the war against al-Qaeda would end when the terrorist group had been weakened so that it was no longer capable of \"strategic attacks\" and had been \"effectively destroyed.\" At that point, the war would no longer be an armed conflict under [[international law]],<ref>{{cite news|author=Julian E. Barnes|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424127887324205404578151181874456280|title=Pentagon Lawyer Looks Post-Terror|date=30 November 2012|newspaper=Wall Street Journal|accessdate=4 December 2012}}</ref>  and the military fight could be replaced by a [[law enforcement]] operation.<ref>{{cite news |title=Pentagon lawyer: War on terror not endless |agency=The Associated Press |url=http://www.lasvegassun.com/news/2012/dec/01/eu-britain-us-al-qaida/ |newspaper=[[Las Vegas Sun]] |publisher=Greenspun Media Group |date=1 December 2012 |accessdate=4 December 2012}}{{Dead link|date=July 2013}}</ref> Johnson had been contemplating the question of \"When does the war end?\" ever since the Chairman of the House Armed Services Committee, [[Ike Skelton]], had posed that question to him several years earlier.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Klaidman|first=Daniel|url=|title=Will Obama End the War on Terror?|date=24 December 2012|work=Newsweek|access-date=|url-status=live|page=29}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2013, two years after the [[Death of Osama bin Laden|assassination]] of [[Osama bin Laden]], Barack Obama delivered a speech that employed the term ''global war on terror'' put in quotation marks (as officially transcribed by the White House): \"Now, make no mistake, our nation is still threatened by terrorists. ... But we have to recognize that the threat has shifted and evolved from the one that came to our shores on 9/11. ... From our use of drones to the detention of terrorist suspects, the decisions that we are making now will define the type of nation\u2014and world\u2014that we leave to our children. So America is at a crossroads. We must define the nature and scope of this struggle, or else it will define us. We have to be mindful of James Madison's warning that \"No nation could preserve its freedom in the midst of continual warfare.\" ... In Afghanistan, we will complete our transition to Afghan responsibility for that country's security. ... Beyond Afghanistan, we must define our effort not as a boundless \"global war on terror,\" but rather as a series of persistent, targeted efforts to dismantle specific networks of violent extremists that threaten America. In many cases, this will involve partnerships with other countries.\" Nevertheless, in the same speech, in a bid to emphasise the legality of military actions undertaken by the U.S., noting that [[Authorization for Use of Military Force Against Terrorists|Congress had authorised]] the use of force, he went on to say, \"Under domestic law, and international law, the United States is at war with al Qaeda, the Taliban, and their associated forces.  We are at war with an organization that right now would kill as many Americans as they could if we did not stop them first. So this is a just war\u2014a war waged proportionally, in last resort, and in self-defense.\"<ref name=whitehdefuniv>[https://obamawhitehouse.archives.gov/the-press-office/2013/05/23/remarks-president-national-defense-university Remarks by the President at the National Defense University] The White House, 23 May 2013.</ref><ref name=terrorover>{{cite news |title=Obama: 'Global War on Terror' Is Over |author=Paul D. Shinkman |url=https://www.usnews.com/news/articles/2013/05/23/obama-global-war-on-terror-is-over?page=2 |newspaper=U.S. News & World Report |date=23 May 2013 |accessdate=24 June 2013}}</ref>\n\n===The rhetorical war on terror===\nBecause the actions involved in the war on terrorism are diffuse, and the criteria for inclusion are unclear, political theorist Richard Jackson has argued that \"the 'war on terrorism,' therefore, is simultaneously a set of actual practices\u2014wars, covert operations, agencies, and institutions\u2014and an accompanying series of assumptions, beliefs, justifications, and narratives\u2014it is an entire language or discourse.\"<ref>Jackson, ''Writing the War on Terrorism'' (2005), p. 8.</ref> Jackson cites among many examples a statement by [[John Ashcroft]] that \"the attacks of September 11 drew a bright line of demarcation between the civil and the savage\".<ref>Jackson, ''Writing the War on Terrorism'' (2005), p. 62.</ref> Administration officials also described \"terrorists\" as hateful, treacherous, barbarous, mad, twisted, perverted, without faith, [[Parasitism|parasitical]], inhuman, and, most commonly, evil.<ref>Jackson, ''Writing the War on Terrorism'' (2005), pp. 62\u201375.</ref> Americans, in contrast, were described as brave, loving, generous, strong, resourceful, heroic, and respectful of human rights.<ref>Jackson, ''Writing the War on Terrorism'' (2005), pp. 77\u201380.</ref>\n\nBoth the term and the policies it denotes have been a source of ongoing controversy, as critics argue it has been used to justify unilateral [[preventive war]], human rights abuses and other violations of international law.<ref>Borhan Uddin Khan and Muhammad Mahbubur Rahman, \"Combating Terrorism under Human Rights and Humanitarian Law Regime\", ''Mediterranean Journal of Human Rights'', Vol. 12 (double issue), 2008, pp.379\u2013397.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.amnestyusa.org/our-work/issues/security-and-human-rights?id=1108209|title= Civil Rights and the \"War on Terror\"|publisher=Amnesty International USA|accessdate=2 May 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\n===Precursor to the 11 September attacks===\n{{See also|Islamic terrorism|List of Islamist terrorist attacks}}\nThe origins of al-Qaeda can be traced back to the [[Soviet\u2013Afghan War]] (December 1979 \u2013 February 1989). The United States, the United Kingdom, Saudi Arabia, [[Pakistan]], and the People's Republic of China supported the Afghan [[mujahideen]] [[guerilla warfare|guerillas]] against the military forces of the Soviet Union and the [[Democratic Republic of Afghanistan]]. A small number of \"Afghan Arab\" volunteers joined the fight against the Soviets, including [[Osama bin Laden]], but there is no evidence they received any external assistance.<ref>{{cite book|last=Bergen|first=Peter|title=The Osama Bin Laden I Know: An Oral History of Al-Qaeda's Leader|publisher=Free Press|year=2006|pages=60\u201361}}</ref> In a 1993 interview, bin Laden himself said that, \u201cPersonally neither I nor my brothers saw evidence of American help.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.factcheck.org/2013/02/rand-pauls-bin-laden-claim-is-urban-myth/|title=Rand Paul's Bin Laden Claim Is 'Urban Myth'|last=|first=|date=|website=FactCheck|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> In May 1996 the group World Islamic Front for Jihad Against Jews and Crusaders (WIFJAJC), sponsored by bin Laden (and later re-formed as al-Qaeda), started forming a large base of operations in [[Afghanistan]], where the Islamist extremist regime of the [[Taliban]] had seized power earlier in the year.<ref>The group was also responsible for the [[1993 World Trade Center bombing]].{{cite news|url=https://articles.latimes.com/2001/dec/06/news/mn-12224|title=Fighters Hunt Former Ally|date=6 December 2001|author=Megan K. Stack|work=Los Angeles Times|accessdate=2 May 2010}}</ref> In August 1996, Bin Laden declared jihad against the United States.<ref>{{cite news |last=Mikelionis |first=Lukas |date=27 April 2018 |title=US already fighting Al Qaeda before 9/11, military judge rules in landmark decision |url=http://www.foxnews.com/us/2018/04/27/us-already-fighting-al-qaeda-before-911-military-judge-rules-in-landmark-decision.html |work=Fox News |location= |access-date=27 April 2018}}<br />{{cite book|author=N. Shah|title=Self-defense in Islamic and International Law: Assessing Al-Qaeda and the Invasion of Iraq|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=db3IAAAAQBAJ&pg=PA46|date=17 March 2008|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan US|isbn=978-0-230-61165-8|page=46}}<br />{{cite book|author=Paul Hopper|title=Living with Globalization|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=cVB2gWNbIXAC&pg=PT72|date=1 March 2006|publisher=Berg|isbn=978-1-84788-613-2|page=72}}<br />{{cite web |url=https://ctc.usma.edu/harmony-program/declaration-of-jihad-against-the-americans-occupying-the-land-of-the-two-holiest-sites-original-language-2/ |title=Declaration of Jihad against the Americans Occupying the Land of the Two Holiest Sites |last=bin Laden |first=Usama |date= |via=Combating Terrorism Center, United States Military Academy |access-date=27 April 2018}}</ref> In February 1998, Osama bin Laden signed a [[fatw\u0101]], as head of al-Qaeda, [[Declaration of war|declaring war]] on the West and [[Israel]];<ref>{{cite news|title=Al Qaeda's Fatwa |url=https://www.pbs.org/newshour/terrorism/international/fatwa_1998.html |newspaper=[[PBS Newshour]] |date=23 February 1998 |accessdate=10 September 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110906040131/https://www.pbs.org/newshour/terrorism/international/fatwa_1998.html |archivedate=6 September 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fbi.gov/news/testimony/al-qaeda-international |title=Al-Qaeda International |author=J. T. Caruso |date=8 December 2001 |publisher=Federal Bureau of Investigation |accessdate=10 September 2011}}</ref> in May al-Qaeda released a video declaring war on the U.S. and the West.<ref>{{cite news |title=Previously unseen tape shows bin Laden's declaration of war |author=Nic Robertson |url=http://articles.cnn.com/2002-08-19/us/terror.tape.main_1_bin-international-islamic-front-osama?_s=PM:US |publisher=CNN |date=19 August 2002 |accessdate=10 September 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110310025036/http://articles.cnn.com/2002-08-19/us/terror.tape.main_1_bin-international-islamic-front-osama?_s=PM%3AUS |archivedate=10 March 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Osama bin Laden: missed opportunities |author=Lisa Myers |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/id/4540958 |publisher=NBC News |date=17 March 2004 |accessdate=10 September 2011}}</ref>\n\nOn 7 August 1998, al-Qaeda [[1998 United States embassy bombings|struck the U.S. embassies in Kenya and Tanzania]], killing 224 people, including 12 Americans.<ref>{{cite news|title=Report of the Accountability Review Boards|publisher=U.S. Department of State|date=7 August 1998|url=https://www.state.gov/www/regions/africa/board_introduction.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20000530211831/http://www.state.gov/www/regions/africa/board_introduction.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=30 May 2000}}</ref> In retaliation, U.S. President [[Bill Clinton]] launched [[Operation Infinite Reach]], a bombing campaign in [[Sudan]] and Afghanistan against targets the U.S. asserted were associated with WIFJAJC,<ref>{{cite news|title=U.S. strikes terrorist targets in Afghanistan, Sudan|publisher=CNN|date=20 August 1998|url=http://edition.cnn.com/US/9808/20/clinton.02/index.html?eref=sitesearch}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=U.S. retaliates for Africa bombings|publisher=CNN|date=20 August 1998|url=http://edition.cnn.com/US/9808/20/clinton.01/index.html?eref=sitesearch}}</ref> although others have questioned whether a pharmaceutical plant in Sudan was used as a chemical warfare facility. The plant produced much of the region's [[antimalarial drug]]s<ref name=\"newstatesman.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.newstatesman.com/200003200023 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071227233133/http://www.newstatesman.com/200003200023|archivedate=27 December 2007|title=Bad air and rank hypocrisy|author=Malcolm Clark|date=20 March 2000|website=New Statesman|accessdate=2 May 2010}}</ref> and around 50% of Sudan's pharmaceutical needs.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://partners.nytimes.com/library/world/africa/082798attack-us.html|title=Possible Benign Use Is Seen for Chemical at Factory in Sudan|author1=Stevel Lee Myers |author2=Tim Weiner |lastauthoramp=yes |date=27 August 1998|work=New York Times|accessdate=2 May 2010}}</ref> The strikes failed to kill any leaders of WIFJAJC or the Taliban.<ref name=\"newstatesman.com\" />\n\nNext came the [[2000 millennium attack plots]], which included an attempted bombing of [[Los Angeles International Airport]]. On 12 October 2000, the [[USS Cole bombing|USS ''Cole'' bombing]] occurred near the port of Yemen, and 17 [[U.S. Navy]] [[sailors]] were killed.<ref>{{cite news|title=What proof of bin Laden's involvement|publisher=CNN|date=13 September 2001|url=http://cnn.com/2001/US/09/13/binladen.evidence/index.html?eref=sitesearch |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120927150633/http://www.cnn.com/2001/US/09/13/binladen.evidence/index.html?eref=sitesearch |archivedate=27 September 2012}}</ref>\n\n===11 September attacks===\n{{Main|September 11 attacks}}\nOn the morning of 11 September 2001, [[Hijackers in the September 11 attacks|nineteen men]] [[Aircraft hijacking|hijacked]] four [[jet airliner]]s all bound for California. Once the hijackers assumed control of the jet airliners, they told the passengers that they had a [[Explosive device|bomb]] on board and would spare the lives of passengers and crew once their demands were met \u2013 no passenger and crew actually suspected that they would use the jet airliners as [[suicide weapon]]s since it had never happened before in history, and many previous hijacking attempts had been resolved with the passengers and crew escaping unharmed after obeying the hijackers.<ref name=\"Holmes\">{{cite book |last=Holmes|first=Stephen|title=Making sense of suicide missions|year=2006|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-929797-9|editor=Diego Gambetta|chapter=Al Qaeda, 11 September 2001}}</ref><ref name=\"Keppel2008\">{{cite book|last=Keppel|first=Gilles|title=Al Qaeda in its own words|year=2008|publisher=Harvard University Press|isbn=978-0-674-02804-3|last2=Milelli|first2=Jean-Pierre|last3=Ghazaleh|first3=Pascale|url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780674028043}}</ref> The hijackers \u2013 members of al-Qaeda's [[Hamburg cell]]<ref>\"[http://www.9-11commission.gov/report/911Report_Ch5.htm Chapter of the 9/11 Commission Report detailing the history of the Hamburg Cell]\". [[9/11 Commission]].</ref> \u2013 intentionally crashed two jet airliners into the Twin Towers of the [[World Trade Center (1973\u20132001)|World Trade Center]] in [[New York City]]. Both buildings collapsed within two hours from fire damage related to the crashes, destroying nearby buildings and damaging others. The hijackers crashed a third jet airliner into [[the Pentagon]] in [[Arlington County, Virginia]], just outside [[Washington, D.C.]] The fourth jet airliner crashed into a field near [[Shanksville, Pennsylvania|Shanksville]], [[Pennsylvania]], after some of its passengers and flight crew attempted to retake control of the jet airliners, which the hijackers had redirected toward Washington D.C., to target the [[White House]] or the [[U.S. Capitol]]. None of the flights had any survivors. A total of 2,977 victims and the 19 hijackers perished in the attacks.<ref>{{cite book |title=The Impact of 9/11 on Politics and War: The Day that Changed Everything? |author=Matthew J. Morgan |page=222|date=4 August 2009 |publisher=Palgrave Macmillan|isbn=978-0-2306-07637}}</ref> Fifteen of the nineteen were citizens of [[Saudi Arabia]], and the others were from the [[United Arab Emirates]] (2), [[Egypt]], and [[Lebanon]].<ref name=\"cia.gov\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cia.gov/news-information/speeches-testimony/2002/DCI_18_June_testimony_new.pdf|title=DCI Testimony Before the Joint Inquiry into Terrorist Attacks Against the United States |date=18 June 2002 |publisher=CIA}}</ref>\n\nOn 13 September, for the first time ever, [[NATO]] invoked [[North Atlantic Treaty#Article 5|Article 5]] of the [[North Atlantic Treaty]], which commits each member state to consider an armed attack against one member state to be an armed attack against them all.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2001/09/13/us/after-attacks-alliance-for-first-time-nato-invokes-joint-defense-pact-with-us.html|title=AFTER THE ATTACKS: THE ALLIANCE; For First Time, NATO Invokes Joint Defense Pact With U.S|first=Suzanne|last=Daley|date=13 September 2001|work=New York Times}}</ref> The invocation of Article 5 led to [[Operation Eagle Assist]] and [[Operation Active Endeavour]]. On 18 September 2001, President Bush signed the [[Authorization for Use of Military Force Against Terrorists]] passed by Congress a few days prior, the authorization is still active and has been used to justify numerous military actions.\n\n==U.S. objectives==\n[[File:Battlefields in The Global War on Terror.svg|thumb|upright=1.6|\n{{legend|#89e885|[[NATO]]}}\n{{legend|#85c3e8|[[Trans-Saharan Counterterrorism Initiative|Trans-Sahara initiative]]}}\n{{legend|#ea7070|Major military operations ('''[[War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)|Afghanistan]] \u2022 [[War in Waziristan|Pakistan]] \u2022 [[Iraq War|Iraq]] \u2022 [[Somali Civil War|Somalia]] \u2022 [[Terrorism in Yemen|Yemen]]''')}}\n{{legend|#bee885|Other allies involved in major operations}}\n[[File:Circle Burgundy Solid.svg|13px]] Major terrorist attacks by al-Qaeda and affiliated groups:\n<small>''1. [[1998 United States embassy bombings]] \u2022 2. [[September 11 attacks|11 September 2001 attacks]] \u2022 3. [[2002 Bali bombings|Bali bombings 2002]]\u2022 4. [[2004 Madrid train bombings|Madrid bombings 2004]] \u2022 5. [[2005 London bombings|London bombings 2005]] \u2022 6. [[2008 Mumbai attacks|Mumbai attacks 2008]]''</small>]]\n\nThe [[Authorization for Use of Military Force Against Terrorists]] or \"AUMF\" was made law on 14 September 2001, to authorize the use of United States Armed Forces against those responsible for the attacks on 11 September 2001. It authorized the President to use all necessary and appropriate force against those nations, organizations, or persons he determines planned, authorized, committed, or aided the terrorist attacks that occurred on 11 September 2001, or harbored such organizations or persons, to prevent any future acts of international terrorism against the United States by such nations, organizations or individuals. Congress declares this is intended to constitute specific statutory authorization within the meaning of section 5(b) of the [[War Powers Resolution]] of 1973.\n\nThe [[George W. Bush administration]] defined the following objectives in the War on Terror:<ref name=\"NatStratCombatTerror\">{{cite web|url=https://georgewbush-whitehouse.archives.gov/news/releases/2003/02/20030214-7.html|title=President Bush Releases National Strategy for Combating Terrorism|date=14 February 2003|publisher=The White House|accessdate=14 September 2014}}</ref>\n\n# Defeat terrorists such as [[Osama bin Laden]], [[Abu Musab al-Zarqawi]] and destroy their organizations\n# Identify, locate and demolish terrorists along with their organizations\n# Reject sponsorship, support and sanctuary to terrorists\n## End the [[state sponsorship of terrorism]]\n## Establish and maintain an international standard of responsibility concerning combating terrorism\n## Strengthen and maintain the international effort to combat terrorism\n## Function with willing and able states\n## Enable weak states\n## Persuade reluctant states\n## Compel unwilling states\n## Intervene and dismantle material support for terrorists\n## Abolish terrorist sanctuaries and havens\n# Reduce the underlying conditions that terrorists seek to exploit\n## Establish partnerships with the international community to strengthen weak states and prevent (re)emergence of terrorism\n## Win the war of ideals\n# Protect U.S. citizens and interests at home and abroad\n## Integrate the [[National Strategy for Homeland Security]]\n## Attain domain awareness\n## Enhance measures to ensure the integrity, reliability, and availability of critical, physical, and information-based infrastructures at home and abroad\n## Implement measures to protect U.S. citizens abroad\n## Ensure an integrated incident management capacity\n\n==Afghanistan==\n===Operation Enduring Freedom===\n{{Main|Operation Enduring Freedom}}\n[[File:Streamer gwotE.PNG|thumb|Campaign streamer awarded to units who have participated in [[Global War on Terrorism Expeditionary Medal|Operation Enduring Freedom]]]]\n\nOperation Enduring Freedom is the official name used by the Bush administration for the [[War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)|War in Afghanistan]], together with three smaller military actions, under the umbrella of the Global War on Terror. [[List of wars and battles involving al-Qaeda|These global operations]] are intended to seek out and destroy any al-Qaeda fighters or affiliates.\n\n===Operation Enduring Freedom \u2013 Afghanistan===\n{{Main|War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)}}\n{{See also|List of military operations in the war in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)}}\nOn 20 September 2001, in the wake of the [[September 11 attacks]], George W. Bush delivered an ultimatum to the Taliban government of Afghanistan, the [[Islamic Emirate of Afghanistan]], to turn over Osama bin Laden and [[al-Qaeda]] leaders operating in the country or face attack.<ref name=\"cnntranscript\" /> The Taliban demanded evidence of bin Laden's link to the 11 September attacks and, if such evidence warranted a trial, they offered to handle such a trial in an Islamic Court.<ref>{{cite news|title=Taliban rejects president Bush's demands |publisher=PBS |date=21 September 2001 |url=https://www.pbs.org/newshour/updates/september01/taliban_9-21.html |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080601224636/https://www.pbs.org/newshour/updates/september01/taliban_9-21.html |archivedate=1 June 2008}}</ref> The U.S. refused to provide any evidence.\n\n[[File:M249 with Mk46 stock.jpg|thumb|left|U.S. Army soldier of the [[10th Mountain Division]] in [[Nuristan Province]], June 2007]]\nSubsequently, in October 2001, U.S. forces (with UK and coalition allies) [[United States invasion of Afghanistan|invaded Afghanistan]] to oust the Taliban regime. On 7 October 2001, the official invasion began with British and U.S. forces conducting [[airstrike]] campaigns over enemy targets. Kabul, the capital city of Afghanistan, [[Fall of Kabul|fell by mid-November]]. The remaining al-Qaeda and Taliban remnants fell back to the rugged mountains of eastern Afghanistan, mainly Tora Bora. In December, Coalition forces (the U.S. and its allies) [[Battle of Tora Bora|fought within that region]]. It is believed that Osama bin Laden escaped into Pakistan during the battle.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/11/29/world/asia/29torabora.html?_r=1 |title=Senate Report Explores 2001 Escape by bin Laden From Afghan Mountains |work=The New York Times |date=28 November 2009 |accessdate=19 January 2011 |first=Scott |last=Shane}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2009/nov/29/osama-bin-laden-senate-report |title=Rumsfeld let Bin Laden escape in 2001, says Senate report |date=29 November 2009 |accessdate=19 January 2011 |first=Ed |last=Pilkington |work=The Guardian |location=London}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2002, the U.S. and other [[NATO]] and non-NATO forces launched [[Operation Anaconda]] with the goal of destroying any remaining al-Qaeda and Taliban forces in the [[Shah-i-Kot Valley]] and [[Arma Mountains]] of Afghanistan. The Taliban suffered heavy casualties and evacuated the region.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.atimes.com/c-asia/DC12Ag01.html |work=[[Asia Times Online]] |date=12 March 2002 |accessdate=19 January 2011 |first=Syed Saleem |last=Shahzad |title=Taliban find unlikely allies}}</ref>\n\nThe Taliban regrouped in western Pakistan and began to unleash an insurgent-style offensive against Coalition forces in late 2002.<ref>{{cite news |publisher=CNN |date=26 March 2002 |accessdate=19 January 2011 |url=http://articles.cnn.com/2002-03-26/us/ret.war.facts_1_taliban-fighters-al-qaeda-afghanistan?_s=PM:US |title=Al Qaeda, Taliban may be regrouping |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110916184950/http://articles.cnn.com/2002-03-26/us/ret.war.facts_1_taliban-fighters-al-qaeda-afghanistan?_s=PM%3AUS |archivedate=16 September 2011}}</ref> Throughout southern and eastern Afghanistan, firefights broke out between the surging Taliban and Coalition forces. Coalition forces responded with a series of military offensives and an increase of troops in Afghanistan. In February 2010, Coalition forces launched [[Operation Moshtarak]] in southern Afghanistan along with other military offensives in the hopes that they would destroy the Taliban insurgency once and for all.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/asia/2010/02/201021343536129252.html |publisher=Al Jazeera English |date=13 February 2010 |accessdate=19 January 2011 |title=Operation Moshtarak: At a glance}}</ref> Peace talks are also underway between Taliban affiliated fighters and Coalition forces.<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Karzai: Afghan forces now in driver's seat, and we're restarting peace talks with Taliban |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/karzai-afghan-forces-now-in-drivers-seat-and-were-restarting-peace-talks-with-taliban/ |publisher=CBS News |date=18 June 2013 |accessdate=14 September 2014}}</ref> In September 2014, Afghanistan and the United States signed a security agreement, which permits the United States and NATO forces to remain in Afghanistan until at least 2024.<ref>{{cite news |last=Ackerman |first=Spencer |date=30 September 2014 |title=New Afghanistan pact means America's longest war will last until at least 2024 |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/sep/30/us-troops-afghanistan-2024-obama-bilateral-security-agreement |newspaper=The Guardian |location=United Kingdom |access-date=7 February 2015}}</ref> The [[Withdrawal of U.S. troops from Afghanistan|United States]] and other NATO and non-NATO forces are planning to [[Withdrawal (military)|withdraw]];<ref>{{cite news |last=DeYoung |first=Karen |date=26 February 2014 |title=Defense ministers say NATO is prepared to withdraw all troops from Afghanistan |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/defense-ministers-say-nato-is-prepared-to-withdraw-all-troops-from-afghanistan/2014/02/26/83c93322-9f01-11e3-878c-65222df220eb_story.html |newspaper=Washington Post |accessdate=14 September 2014}}<br />{{cite news |last=Graham-Harrison |first=Emma |date=4 September 2014 |title=Afghanistan security forces' readiness for Nato withdrawal still a hard sell |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2013/sep/04/afghanistan-security-forces-nato-withdrawal |newspaper=The Guardian |location=Kabul |accessdate=14 September 2014}}</ref> with the Taliban claiming it has defeated the United States and NATO,<ref>{{cite news |last=Ruble |first=Kayla |date=29 December 2014 |title=Taliban Claims 'Defeat' of US and Allies in Afghanistan as NATO Withdraws Troops |url=https://news.vice.com/article/taliban-claims-defeat-of-us-and-allies-in-afghanistan-as-nato-withdraws-troops |newspaper=Vice |access-date=7 February 2015}}<br />{{cite news |last=Sedghi |first=Sarah |date=30 December 2014 |title=Taliban claims victory as NATO withdraws from Afghanistan |url=http://www.abc.net.au/am/content/2014/s4155592.htm |publisher=ABC |location=Australia |access-date=7 February 2015}}<br />{{cite news |last=Johnson |first=Kay |last2=Macfie |first2=Nick |date=29 December 2015 |title=Taliban declare 'defeat' of U.S., allies in Afghanistan |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2014/12/29/us-afghanistan-war-idUSKBN0K70UC20141229 |publisher=Reuters |access-date=7 February 2015}}</ref> and the [[Obama Administration]] viewing it as a victory.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Makarechi |first=Kia |date=29 December 2014 |title=Obama Has a Curious Definition for the End of War |url=https://www.vanityfair.com/news/politics/2014/12/obama-end-of-afghan-war |journal=Vanity Fair |access-date=8 February 2015}}</ref> In December 2014, ISAF encasing its colors, and [[Resolute Support Mission|Resolute Support]] began as the NATO operation in Afghanistan.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nato.int/cps/en/natohq/topics_113694.htm |title=NATO-led Resolute Support Mission in Afghanistan |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=30 January 2015 |publisher=NATO |accessdate=7 February 2015}}<br />{{cite news |last=Smith |first=Josh |date=16 December 2014 |title=NATO mission in Afghanistan unlikely to change much |url=http://www.stripes.com/news/nato-mission-in-afghanistan-unlikely-to-change-much-1.319624 |newspaper=Stars & Stripes |access-date=7 February 2015}}</ref> Continued United States operations within Afghanistan will continue under the name \"Operation Freedom's Sentinel\".<ref>{{cite news |last=Lamothe |first=Dan |date=29 December 2014 |title=Meet Operation Freedom's Sentinel, the Pentagon's new mission in Afghanistan |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/checkpoint/wp/2014/12/29/meet-operation-freedoms-sentinel-the-pentagons-new-mission-in-afghanistan/ |newspaper=Washington Post |accessdate=2 January 2015}}</ref>\n\n===International Security Assistance Force===\n{{Main|International Security Assistance Force}}\n[[File:ISAF map.svg|thumb|Map of countries contributing troops to ISAF as of 5 March 2010. Major contributors (over 1000 troops) in dark green, other contributors in light green, and former contributors in magenta.]]\nThe NATO-led [[International Security Assistance Force]] (ISAF) was created in December 2001 to assist the [[Afghan Transitional Administration]] and the first post-Taliban elected government. With a renewed Taliban insurgency, it was announced in 2006 that ISAF would replace the U.S. troops in the province as part of Operation Enduring Freedom.\n\nThe British [[16th Air Assault Brigade]] (later reinforced by [[Royal Marines]]) formed the core of the force in southern Afghanistan, along with troops and helicopters from Australia, Canada and the Netherlands. The initial force consisted of roughly 3,300 British, 2,000 Canadian, 1,400 from the Netherlands and 240 from Australia, along with special forces from Denmark and [[Estonia]] and small contingents from other nations. The monthly supply of cargo containers through Pakistani route to ISAF in Afghanistan is over 4,000 costing around {{nowrap|12 billion}} in Pakistani Rupees.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thenewstribe.com/2011/01/29/war-on-terror-cost-of-us-taxpayers-patience/#.TtjwPLLNllk |title=Afghan war cost rise tests US taxpayers' patience |publisher=Thenewstribe.com |date=29 January 2011 |accessdate=2 January 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=UK troops take over Afghan duties|date=1 June 2006|publisher=BBC|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/4961368.stm}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Canada set for longer Afghan stay |date=16 June 2006 |publisher=BBC |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/4984880.stm}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Australia outlines Afghan force|date=8 May 2006|publisher=BBC|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/4983540.stm}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=More Dutch troops for Afghanistan |date=3 February 2006 |publisher=BBC |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/4673026.stm}}</ref>\n\n==Iraq and Syria==\n{{further|Iraq War and the War on Terror}}\n\n[[Iraq]] had been listed as a [[State sponsor of terrorism]] by the U.S. since 1990,<ref>{{cite news|title=Iraq accuses U.S., Turkey of 'illegally' meeting with Kurds |publisher=CNN |date=9 March 2000 |url=http://archives.cnn.com/2000/WORLD/meast/03/09/un.iraq/index.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080516120925/http://archives.cnn.com/2000/WORLD/meast/03/09/un.iraq/index.html |archivedate=16 May 2008}}</ref> when [[Saddam Hussein]] [[invasion of Kuwait|invaded Kuwait]]. Iraq had also been on the list from 1979 to 1982; it was removed so that the U.S. could provide material support to Iraq in its [[Iran\u2013Iraq War|war with Iran]]. Hussein's regime had proven to be a problem for the UN and Iraq's neighbors due to its use of [[chemical weapons]] against [[Iranian people|Iranians]] and [[Kurds]] in the 1980s.\n\n===Iraqi no-fly zones===\nFollowing the ceasefire agreement that suspended hostilities (but not officially ended) in the 1991 [[Gulf War]], the United States and its allies instituted and began patrolling [[Iraqi no-fly zones]], to protect Iraq's [[Kurds|Kurdish]] and [[Shi'a]] [[Arab]] population\u2014both of which suffered attacks from the Hussein regime before and after the Gulf War\u2014in Iraq's northern and southern regions, respectively. U.S. forces continued in combat zone deployments through November 1995 and launched [[Operation Desert Fox]] against Iraq in 1998 after it failed to meet U.S. demands for \"unconditional cooperation\" in weapons inspections.<ref>{{cite news|title=Clinton: Iraq has abused its final chance |publisher=CNN |date=16 December 1998 |url=http://www.cnn.com/ALLPOLITICS/stories/1998/12/16/clinton/index.html?eref=sitesearch}}</ref>\n\nIn the aftermath of Operation Desert Fox, during December 1998, Iraq announced that it would no longer respect the no-fly zones and resumed its attempts to shoot down U.S. aircraft.\n\n===Operation Iraqi Freedom===\n{{Main|Iraq War}}\n[[File:C-130J Hercules, Iraq, 2003.jpg|thumb|A British [[C-130J Hercules]] aircraft launches [[Flare (countermeasure)|flare countermeasures]] before being the first coalition aircraft to land on the newly reopened military runway at [[Baghdad International Airport]]]]\nThe Iraq War began in March 2003 with an air campaign, which was immediately followed by a [[2003 invasion of Iraq|U.S.-led ground invasion]]. The Bush administration cited UNSC Resolution 1441, which warned of \"serious consequences\" for violations such as [[Iraq and weapons of mass destruction|Iraq possessing weapons of mass destruction]]. The Bush administration also [[Iraq War and U.S. Global War on Terror|stated the Iraq war]] was part of the War on Terror, a claim later [[Criticism of the War on Terror|questioned and contested]].\n\nThe first ground attack came at the [[Battle of Umm Qasr]] on 21 March 2003, when a combined force of British, U.S. and Polish forces seized control of the port city of [[Umm Qasr]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Parker |first=Nick |last2=McCarthy |first2=Rory |date=23 March 2003 |title=Fierce battle around port |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2003/mar/24/iraq.rorymccarthy |newspaper=The Guardian |access-date=17 March 2015}}<br />{{cite book|author=Mike Ryan|title=Baghdad or Bust|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=AhjOAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA136|date=4 December 2003|publisher=Pen and Sword|isbn=978-1-84415-020-5|pages=136\u2013137}}<br />{{cite book|author=Leigh Neville|title=Special Operations Forces in Iraq|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Cqi3yVGkDZ8C&pg=PA10|date=1 January 2012|publisher=Osprey Publishing|isbn=978-1-84908-826-8|pages=10\u201311}}</ref> [[Baghdad]], Iraq's capital city, [[Battle of Baghdad (2003)|fell to U.S. troops]] in April 2003 and Saddam Hussein's government quickly dissolved.<ref>{{cite book|author1=Mary Beth Norton|author2=Carol Sheriff|author3=David M. Katzman |author4=David W. Blight |author5=Howard Chudacoff|title=A People and a Nation: A History of the United States, Brief Edition|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=BMxIyj05MIQC&pg=PA895|date=30 December 2008|publisher=Cengage Learning|isbn=978-0-547-17558-4|page=895}}<br />{{cite book|author=John Ehrenberg|title=The Iraq Papers|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=AyQRB6Iov70C&pg=PT219|date=1 January 2010|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-539858-8|pages=219\u2013225}}</ref> On 1 May 2003, [[2003 Mission Accomplished speech|Bush announced]] that major combat operations in Iraq had ended.<ref>{{cite press release |publisher=The White House |date=1 May 2003 |title=President Bush Announces Major Combat Operations in Iraq Have Ended |url=https://georgewbush-whitehouse.archives.gov/news/releases/2003/05/print/20030501-15.html}}</ref> However, an insurgency arose against the U.S.-led coalition and the newly developing Iraqi military and post-Saddam government. The rebellion, which included [[Al-Qaeda in Iraq|al-Qaeda-affiliated groups]], led to far more coalition casualties [[Post-invasion Iraq, 2003\u2013present|than the invasion]]. Other elements of the insurgency were led by fugitive members of President Hussein's [[Ba'ath]] regime, which included Iraqi nationalists and [[pan-Arabist]]s. Many insurgency leaders were [[Islamists]] and claimed to be fighting a religious war to reestablish the Islamic [[Caliphate]] of centuries past.<ref>{{cite news|author=Michael Ware|url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,1101040705-658290,00.html |title=Meet The New Jihad |work=Time |date=27 June 2004 |accessdate=26 March 2011}}</ref> Saddam Hussein [[Operation Red Dawn|was captured by U.S. forces]] in December 2003 and [[Execution of Saddam Hussein|was executed]] in 2006.\n\nIn 2004, the insurgent forces grew stronger. The U.S. launched offensives on insurgent strongholds in cities like [[Battle of Najaf (2004)|Najaf]] and [[Second Battle of Fallujah|Fallujah]].\n\nIn January 2007, President Bush presented a new strategy for Operation Iraqi Freedom based upon [[counter-insurgency]] theories and tactics developed by General [[David Petraeus]]. The [[Iraq War troop surge of 2007]] was part of this \"new way forward\", which along with U.S. backing of [[Sunni]] groups it had previously sought to defeat has been credited with a widely recognized dramatic decrease in violence by up to 80%.{{citation needed|date=July 2019}} \n\nIn 2011, all American troops were withdrawn from Iraq, terminating [[Operation New Dawn (Iraq, 2010-2011)|Operation NEW DAWN]].\n\n===Operation New Dawn===\nThe war entered a new phase on 1 September 2010,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.csmonitor.com/World/Middle-East/2010/0819/Iraq-war-Last-US-combat-brigade-crosses-into-Kuwait |title=Iraq war: Last US combat brigade crosses into Kuwait |website=Christian Science Monitor |date=19 August 2010 |accessdate=26 March 2011}}</ref> with the official end of U.S. combat operations. The last U.S. troops [[Withdrawal of U.S. troops from Iraq (2007\u20132011)|exited Iraq]] on 18 December 2011.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/12/16/world/middleeast/panetta-in-baghdad-for-iraq-military-handover-ceremony.html |work=The New York Times |first1=Thom |last1=Shanker |first2=Michael S. |last2=Schmidt |first3=Robert F. |last3=Worth |title=In Baghdad, Panetta Leads Uneasy Closure to Conflict |date=15 December 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Operation Inherent Resolve (Syria and Iraq)===\n{{Main|Operation Inherent Resolve|Military intervention against ISIL|List of wars and battles involving ISIL}}\n{{See|Timeline of the Iraq War (2014)|Spillover of the Syrian Civil War|American-led intervention in Syria|American-led intervention in Iraq (2014\u2013present)}}\n[[File:Tomahawk Missile fired from US Destroyers.jpg|thumb|[[Tomahawk missile]]s being fired from {{USS|Philippine Sea|CG-58|6}} and {{USS|Arleigh Burke}} at IS targets in [[Syria]]]]\nIn a major split in the ranks of Al Qaeda's organization, the Iraqi franchise, known as [[Al Qaeda in Iraq]] covertly invaded Syria and the Levant and began participating in the ongoing Syrian Civil War, gaining enough support and strength to re-invade Iraq's western provinces under the name of the [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant]] (ISIS/ISIL), taking over much of the country in a [[blitzkrieg]]-like action and combining the [[Iraqi insurgency (2011\u201314)|Iraq insurgency]] and [[Syrian Civil War]] into a single conflict.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ctc.usma.edu/posts/ctc-perspectives-al-baghdadis-blitzkrieg-isils-psychological-warfare-and-what-it-means-for-syria-and-iraq |title=CTC Perspectives: Al-Baghdadi's Blitzkrieg, ISIL's Psychological Warfare, and What it Means for Syria and Iraq |last1=Price |first1=Bryan |last2=Milton |first2=Dan |last3=al-'Ubaydi |first3=Muhammad |date=12 June 2014 |website=Combating Terrorism Center |publisher=United States Military Academy |accessdate=14 September 2014}}</ref> Due to their extreme brutality and a complete change in their overall ideology, Al Qaeda's core organization in Central Asia eventually denounced ISIS and directed their affiliates to cut off all ties with this organization.<ref>{{cite news |last=Calamur |first=Krishnadev |date=13 June 2014 |title=ISIS: An Islamist Group Too Extreme Even For Al-Qaida |url=https://www.npr.org/blogs/thetwo-way/2014/06/13/321665375/isis-an-islamist-group-too-extreme-even-for-al-qaida |publisher=National Public Radio |accessdate=14 September 2014}}</ref> Many analysts{{who|date=September 2014}} believe that because of this schism, Al Qaeda and ISIL are now in a competition to retain the title of the world's most powerful terrorist organization.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.washingtoninstitute.org/policy-analysis/view/the-war-between-isis-and-al-qaeda-for-supremacy-of-the-global-jihadist|title=The War between ISIS and al-Qaeda for Supremacy of the Global Jihadist Movement |publisher=The Washington Institute for Near East Policy|date=June 2014|author=Aaron Zelin|accessdate=14 September 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe Obama administration began to re-engage in Iraq with a series of airstrikes aimed at ISIS starting on 10 August 2014.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Sedghi |first1=Ami |last2=Arnett |first2=George |title=US military Isis air strikes in Iraq: day-by-day breakdown |url=https://www.theguardian.com/news/datablog/2014/aug/27/us-military-isis-air-strikes-in-iraq-day-by-day-breakdown |newspaper=The Guardian |date=3 September 2014 |accessdate=14 September 2014}}</ref> On 9 September 2014, President Obama said that he had the authority he needed to take action to destroy the militant group known as the [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant]], citing the 2001 Authorization for the Use of Military Force Against Terrorists, and thus did not require additional approval from Congress.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lamarque |first1=Kevin |title=Obama tells lawmakers he has authorization for Islamic State fight |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2014/09/09/us-iraq-security-obama-meeting-idUSKBN0H42FW20140909 |publisher=Reuters |accessdate=9 September 2014 |date=9 September 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140909221941/https://www.reuters.com/article/2014/09/09/us-iraq-security-obama-meeting-idUSKBN0H42FW20140909 |archivedate=9 September 2014}}</ref> The following day on 10 September 2014 President Barack Obama made a televised speech about ISIL, which he stated: \"Our objective is clear: We will degrade, and ultimately destroy, ISIL through a comprehensive and sustained counter-terrorism strategy\".<ref name=\"ObamaSpeech10SEP14\">{{cite news |last=Shinkman |first=Paul D. |date=10 September 2014 |title=Obama Unveils New Islamic State Strategy |url=https://www.usnews.com/news/articles/2014/09/10/obama-unveils-new-islamic-state-strategy |newspaper=U.S. News & World Report |accessdate=14 September 2014}}</ref> Obama has authorized the deployment of additional U.S. Forces into Iraq, as well as authorizing direct military operations against ISIL within Syria.<ref name=\"ObamaSpeech10SEP14\" /> On the night of 21/22 September the United States, Saudi Arabia, Bahrain, the UAE, Jordan and Qatar started air attacks against ISIS in Syria.{{citation needed|date=October 2014}}\n\nIn October 2014, it was reported that the U.S. Department of Defense considers military operations against ISIL as being under Operation Enduring Freedom in regards to campaign medal awarding.<ref>{{cite news |last=Tilghman |first=Andrew |date=2 October 2014 |title=Pentagon: Medals for new Iraq mission to fall under Operation Enduring Freedom |url=http://www.armytimes.com/article/20141002/NEWS05/310020070/Pentagon-Medals-new-Iraq-mission-fall-under-Operation-Enduring-Freedom |newspaper=Army Times |publisher=Gannett |accessdate=4 October 2014}}</ref> On 15 October, the military intervention became known as \"Operation Inherent Resolve\".<ref>{{cite news|last1=Rhodan|first1=Maya|title=U.S. Military Action Against ISIS Deemed 'Operation Inherent Resolve'|url=http://time.com/3511264/operation-inherent-resolve-isis-iraq-syria/|website=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|accessdate=16 October 2014|date=15 October 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Pakistan==\n{{Main|Pakistan's role in the War on Terror}}\n{{See also|Pakistan\u2013United States relations|Pakistan and state-sponsored terrorism|Insurgency in Khyber Pakhtunkhwa|Drone strikes in Pakistan|Death of Osama bin Laden}}\nFollowing the 11 September 2001 attacks, former President of Pakistan [[Pervez Musharraf]] sided with the U.S. against the Taliban government in Afghanistan after an ultimatum by then U.S. President George W. Bush. Musharraf agreed to give the U.S. the use of three airbases for Operation Enduring Freedom. [[United States Secretary of State]] [[Colin Powell]] and other U.S. administration officials met with Musharraf. On 19 September 2001, Musharraf addressed the people of Pakistan and stated that, while he opposed military tactics against the Taliban, Pakistan risked being endangered by an alliance of India and the U.S. if it did not cooperate. In 2006, Musharraf testified that this stance was pressured by threats from the U.S., and revealed in his memoirs that he had \"war-gamed\" the United States as an adversary and decided that it would end in a loss for Pakistan.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.usatoday.com/news/world/2006-09-25-pakistan-memoir_x.htm|title= Musharraf's book says Pakistan faced U.S. 'onslaught' if it didn't back terror war|accessdate=14 September 2014|work=USA Today|date=26 September 2006}}</ref>\n\nOn 12 January 2002, Musharraf gave a speech against Islamic extremism. He unequivocally condemned all acts of terrorism and pledged to combat Islamic extremism and lawlessness within Pakistan itself. He stated that his government was committed to rooting out extremism and made it clear that the banned militant organizations would not be allowed to resurface under any new name. He said, \"the recent decision to ban extremist groups promoting militancy was taken in the national interest after thorough consultations. It was not taken under any foreign influence\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://archives.dawn.com/dawnftp/72.249.57.55/dawnftp/fixed/arch/arch_2003.html |title=Musharraf vows to root out extremism: Banned outfits won't be allowed to resurface |publisher=Dawn.Com |date=5 December 2003 |first=Rafaqat |last=Ali |accessdate=26 March 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110317081424/http://archives.dawn.com/dawnftp/72.249.57.55/dawnftp/fixed/arch/arch_2003.html |archivedate=17 March 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn 2002, the Musharraf-led government took a firm stand against the jihadi organizations and groups promoting extremism, and arrested [[Maulana Masood Azhar]], head of the [[Jaish-e-Mohammed]], and [[Hafiz Muhammad Saeed]], chief of the [[Lashkar-e-Taiba]], and took dozens of activists into custody. An official ban was imposed on the groups on 12 January.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.atimes.com/atimes/South_Asia/DH20Df07.html |title=Musharraf braced for jihadi backlash |work=Asia Times |date=20 August 2002 |accessdate=26 March 2011}}</ref> Later that year, the [[Saudi Arabia|Saudi]] born [[Abu Zubaydah|Zayn al-Abidn Muhammed Hasayn Abu Zubaydah]] was arrested by Pakistani officials during a series of joint U.S.-Pakistan raids. Zubaydah is said to have been a high-ranking al-Qaeda official with the title of operations chief and in charge of running al-Qaeda training camps.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://archives.cnn.com/2002/WORLD/asiapcf/south/04/01/pakistan.alqaeda/|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061216104729/http://archives.cnn.com/2002/WORLD/asiapcf/south/04/01/pakistan.alqaeda/|archivedate=16 December 2006 |publisher=CNN |title=Officials: Captured man says he's al Qaeda brass |date=1 April 2002 |accessdate=9 April 2010}}</ref> Other prominent al-Qaeda members were arrested in the following two years, namely [[Ramzi bin al-Shibh]], who is known to have been a financial backer of al-Qaeda operations, and [[Khalid Sheikh Mohammed]], who at the time of his capture was the third highest-ranking official in al-Qaeda and had been directly in charge of the planning for the 11 September attacks.\n\nIn 2004, the [[Pakistan Army]] launched a campaign in the [[Federally Administered Tribal Areas]] of Pakistan's [[Waziristan]] region, sending in 80,000 troops. The goal of the conflict was to remove the al-Qaeda and Taliban forces in the area.\n\nAfter the fall of the Taliban regime, many members of the Taliban resistance fled to the Northern border region of Afghanistan and Pakistan where the Pakistani army had previously little control. With the logistics and air support of the United States, the Pakistani Army captured or killed numerous al-Qaeda operatives such as Khalid Sheikh Mohammed, wanted for his involvement in the USS ''Cole'' bombing, the [[Bojinka plot]], and the killing of ''[[Wall Street Journal]]'' reporter [[Daniel Pearl]].\n\nThe United States has carried out a campaign of [[Drone attacks in Pakistan|drone attacks]] on targets all over the Federally Administered Tribal Areas. However, the [[Tehrik-i-Taliban Pakistan|Pakistani Taliban]] still operates there. To this day it is estimated that 15 U.S. soldiers were killed while fighting al-Qaeda and Taliban remnants in Pakistan since the War on Terror began.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://icasualties.org/oef/ |title=Operation Enduring Freedom &#124; Afghanistan |publisher=iCasualties |date=28 May 2010 |accessdate=26 March 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100406083558/http://icasualties.org/oef/ |archivedate=6 April 2010}}</ref>\n\nOsama bin Laden, who was of many founders of al-Qaeda, his wife, and son, were all killed on 2 May 2011, during a raid conducted by the [[United States special operations forces]] in [[Abbottabad]], Pakistan.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailynews.co.zw/index.php/international-news/global-news/2348-bin-laden-shot-in-the-head-and-chest.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120118192058/http://www.dailynews.co.zw/index.php/international-news/global-news/2348-bin-laden-shot-in-the-head-and-chest.html|archivedate=18 January 2012 |title=Bin Laden 'shot in the head and chest' |publisher=Dailynews.co.zw |date=3 May 2011 |accessdate=2 January 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe use of drones by the Central Intelligence Agency in Pakistan to carry out operations associated with the Global War on Terror sparks debate over sovereignty and the laws of war. The U.S. Government uses the CIA rather than the [[U.S. Air Force]] for strikes in Pakistan to avoid breaching sovereignty through military invasion. The United States was criticized by{{according to whom|date=May 2015}} a report on drone warfare and [[Airspace|aerial sovereignty]] for abusing the term 'Global War on Terror' to carry out military operations through government agencies without formally declaring war.\n\nIn the three years before the attacks of 11 September, Pakistan received approximately {{nowrap|US$9 million}} in American military aid. In the three years after, the number increased to {{nowrap|US$4.2 billion}}, making it the country with the maximum funding post 9/11.\n\n===Baluchistan===\n\nVarious NGOs have reported human rights violations in committed by Pakistani armed forces. Approximately 18,000 Baluch residents are reportedly missing and about 2000 have been killed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thediplomat.com/2014/01/balochistans-missing-persons/|title=Balochistan's Missing Persons|author=Kiran Nazish |work=The Diplomat|date=6 January 2014}}</ref>\n\n[[Brahamdagh Bugti]], leader of the [[Baloch Republican Party]], stated in a 2008 interview that he would accept aid from India, Afghanistan, and Iran in defending Baluchistan against Pakistani aggression.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.oneindia.in/2008/07/24/bugtis-grandson-ready-to-accept-help-from-india-1216875825.html|title=Bugti's grandson ready to accept help from India |publisher=News.oneindia.in|date=24 July 2008|accessdate=19 May 2012}}</ref> Pakistan has repeatedly accused India of supporting Baloch rebels,<ref name=ca>{{cite web|last=Butt|first=Qaiser|url=http://tribune.com.pk/story/225958/balochistan-conflict-pms-talks-with-leaders-unlikely-to-succeed/|title=Balochistan conflict: 'PM's talks with leaders unlikely to succeed'|website=The Express Tribune|accessdate=17 December 2011}}</ref><ref name=cb>{{cite web|url=http://www.indianexpress.com/news/no-evidence-that-india-aiding-pak-baloch-rebels/466814/|title=No evidence that India aiding Pak Baloch rebels|website=The Indian Express|date=27 May 2009|accessdate=21 December 2010}}</ref> and David Wright-Neville writes that outside Pakistan, some Western observers also believe that India secretly funds the [[Balochistan Liberation Army]] (BLA).<ref name=Wright-Neville>{{cite book|title=Dictionary of Terrorism|publisher=Polity|isbn=978-0745643021|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZgmXxoLHv8MC&pg=PA48#v=onepage&q&f=false|author=David Wright-Neville|edition=1st|accessdate=3 June 2012|pages=48\u201349|date=11 May 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Trans-Sahara (Northern Africa)==\n===Operation Enduring Freedom&nbsp;\u2013 Trans Sahara===\n{{Main|Operation Enduring Freedom \u2013 Trans Sahara}}\n[[File:Northern Mali conflict.svg|thumb]]\nOperation Enduring Freedom \u2013 Trans Sahara (OEF-TS) is the name of the military operation conducted by the U.S. and partner nations in the Sahara/Sahel region of Africa, consisting of counter-terrorism efforts and policing of arms and drug trafficking across central Africa.\n\nThe [[Northern Mali conflict (2012\u2013present)|conflict in northern Mali]] began in January 2012 with radical Islamists (affiliated to al-Qaeda) advancing into northern Mali. The Malian government had a hard time maintaining full control over their country. The fledgling government requested support from the international community on combating the Islamic militants. In January 2013, France intervened on behalf of the Malian government's request and deployed troops into the region. They launched [[Operation Serval]] on 11 January 2013, with the hopes of dislodging the al-Qaeda affiliated groups from northern Mali.<ref>{{cite news|title=Mali conflict: militants killed as French air strikes pound rebel camps |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2013/jan/13/mali-crisis-militants-killed-french-jets|newspaper=The Guardian|date=14 January 2013|location=London|first=Nick|last=Hopkins}}</ref>\n\n==Horn of Africa and the Red Sea==\n===Operation Enduring Freedom&nbsp;\u2013 Horn of Africa===\n{{Main|Operation Enduring Freedom \u2013 Horn of Africa}}\n{{See also|Somali Civil War (2006\u20132009)|Somali Civil War (2009\u2013present)|Piracy off the coast of Somalia|Drone strikes in Somalia}}\nThis extension of Operation Enduring Freedom was titled OEF-HOA. Unlike other operations contained in Operation Enduring Freedom, OEF-HOA does not have a specific organization as a target. OEF-HOA instead focuses its efforts to disrupt and detect militant activities in the region and to work with willing governments to prevent the reemergence of militant cells and activities.<ref>{{cite news |title=COMBINED JOINT TASK FORCE\u2013HORN OF AFRICA |publisher=United States Africa Command |url=http://www.hoa.africom.mil/AboutCJTF-HOA.asp |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090426223216/http://www.hoa.africom.mil/AboutCJTF-HOA.asp |archivedate=26 April 2009 |accessdate=19 January 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2002, the [[Combined Joint Task Force - Horn of Africa]] (CJTF-HOA) was established in [[Djibouti]] at [[Camp Lemonnier]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.gao.gov/new.items/d10504.pdf |title=DOD Needs to Determine the Future of Its Horn of Africa Task Force |publisher=[[Government Accountability Office]] |date=April 2010|accessdate=19 January 2011}}</ref> It contains approximately 2,000 personnel including U.S. military and special operations forces (SOF) and coalition force members, [[Combined Task Force 150]] (CTF-150).\n\nTask Force 150 consists of ships from a shifting group of nations, including Australia, Canada, France, Germany, Italy, Netherlands, Pakistan, New Zealand and the United Kingdom. The primary goal of the coalition forces is to monitor, inspect, board and stop suspected shipments from entering the Horn of Africa region and affecting the United States' [[Operation Iraqi Freedom]].\n\nIncluded in the operation is the training of selected armed forces units of the countries of Djibouti, [[Kenya]] and [[Ethiopia]] in counter-terrorism and [[counter-insurgency]] tactics. Humanitarian efforts conducted by CJTF-HOA include rebuilding of schools and medical clinics and providing medical services to those countries whose forces are being trained.\n\nThe program expands as part of the [[Trans-Saharan Counterterrorism Initiative]] as CJTF personnel also assist in training the armed forces of [[Chad]], Niger, [[Mauritania]] and [[Mali]]. However, the War on Terror does not include Sudan, where over 400,000 have died in an ongoing civil war.\n\nOn 1 July 2006, a Web-posted message purportedly written by Osama bin Laden urged [[Somalis]] to build an [[Islamic state]] in the country and warned western governments that the al-Qaeda network would fight against them if they intervened there.<ref name=\"BIN-LADEN-MESSAGE-IRAQ-SOMALIA\">{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/news/world/2006-07-01-bin-laden-plans-message_x.htm |title=Bin Laden releases Web message on Iraq, Somalia |work=USA Today |date=1 July 2006 |accessdate=2 January 2012}}</ref>\n\nSomalia has been considered a \"[[failed state]]\" because its official central government was weak, dominated by warlords and unable to exert effective control over the country. Beginning in mid-2006, the Islamic Courts Union (ICU), an Islamist faction campaigning on a restoration of \"law and order\" through [[Sharia]] law, had rapidly taken control of much of southern Somalia.\n\nOn 14 December 2006, the U.S. Assistant Secretary of State [[Jendayi Frazer]] claimed al-Qaeda cell operatives were controlling the Islamic Courts Union, a claim denied by the ICU.<ref name=\"US-SAYS-AL-QAEDA-BEHIND-SOMALI-ISLAMISTS\">{{cite web|url=http://www.alertnet.org/thenews/newsdesk/L14556061.htm |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080204082431/http://www.alertnet.org/thenews/newsdesk/L14556061.htm |archivedate=4 February 2008 |title=U.S. says al Qaeda behind Somali Islamists |date=4 February 2008 |accessdate=2 January 2012}}</ref>\n\nBy late 2006, the UN-backed [[Transitional Federal Government]] (TFG) of Somalia had seen its power effectively limited to [[Baidoa]], while the Islamic Courts Union controlled the majority of southern Somalia, including the capital of [[Mogadishu]]. On 20 December 2006, the Islamic Courts Union launched an [[Battle of Baidoa|offensive]] on the government stronghold of Baidoa and saw early gains before Ethiopia intervened for the government.\n\nBy 26 December, the Islamic Courts Union retreated towards Mogadishu, before again retreating as TFG/Ethiopian troops neared, leaving them to take Mogadishu with [[Fall of Mogadishu|no resistance]]. The ICU then fled to [[Kismayo]], where they fought Ethiopian/TFG forces in the [[Battle of Jilib]].\n\nThe Prime Minister of Somalia claimed that three \"terror suspects\" from the [[1998 United States embassy bombings]] are being sheltered in Kismayo.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2004/jun/13/usa.terrorism |work=The Guardian |location=London |title=Secret world of US jails |first=Jason |last=Burke |date=13 June 2004 |accessdate=9 April 2010}}</ref> On 30 December 2006, al-Qaeda deputy leader [[Ayman al-Zawahiri]] called upon Muslims worldwide to fight against Ethiopia and the TFG in Somalia.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/cfr/world/slot2_20090227.html?_r=1|title=Backgrounder: Al-Shabaab |work=The New York Times|author=Stephanie Hanson|date=2 March 2009|accessdate=4 May 2010}}</ref>\n\nOn 8 January 2007, the U.S. launched the [[Battle of Ras Kamboni]] by bombing [[Ras Kamboni]] using [[AC-130]] gunships.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,242460,00.html |title=U.S. Launches Attack on Suspected Al Qaeda Members in Somalia |publisher=Fox News |date=9 January 2007 |accessdate=26 March 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111106210324/http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,242460,00.html |archive-date=6 November 2011 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nOn 14 September 2009, [[Special Forces (United States Army)|U.S. Special Forces]] killed two men and wounded and captured two others near the Somali village of [[Baraawe raid|Baarawe]]. Witnesses claim that helicopters used for the operation launched from French-flagged warships, but that could not be confirmed. A Somali-based al-Qaida affiliated group, the [[Al-Shabaab (militant group)|Al-Shabaab]], has verified the death of \"sheik commander\" [[Saleh Ali Saleh Nabhan]] along with an unspecified number of militants.<ref>{{cite news |first=Maamoun |last=Youssef |title=Somali al-Qaida group confirms death of leader |url=http://www.armytimes.com/news/2009/09/ap_somalia_alqaida_091609w/ |agency=Associated Press |date=16 September 2009 |accessdate=17 September 2009}}</ref> Nabhan, a Kenyan, was wanted in connection with the [[2002 Mombasa attacks]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Mother demands to see Nabhan's body |url=http://www.aljazeera.com/focus/2009/09/200991691418738699.html |publisher=Al Jazerra |date=16 September 2009 |accessdate=17 September 2009}}</ref>\n\n==Philippines==\n===Operation Enduring Freedom \u2013 Philippines===\n{{Main|Operation Enduring Freedom \u2013 Philippines}}\n[[File:SF Soldier in Philippines.jpg|thumb|[[U.S. Special Forces]] soldier and infantrymen of the [[Philippine Army]]]]\nIn January 2002, the [[United States Special Operations Command|United States Special Operations Command, Pacific]] deployed to the [[Philippines]] to advise and assist the [[Armed Forces of the Philippines]] in combating Filipino Islamist groups.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.socpac.socom.mil/default.aspx |title=Guardians of the Pacific |date=3 January 2009 |accessdate=19 January 2011 |publisher=[[Special Operations Command, Pacific]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110111053550/http://www.socpac.socom.mil/default.aspx |archivedate=11 January 2011}}</ref> The operations were mainly focused on removing the [[Abu Sayyaf]] group and [[Jemaah Islamiyah]] (JI) from their stronghold on the island of [[Basilan]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.globalsecurity.org/military/agency/dod/jsotf-p.htm |title=Joint Special Operations Task Force \u2013 Philippines (JSOTF-P) |publisher=GlobalSecurity.org}}</ref> The second portion of the operation was conducted as a humanitarian program called \"Operation Smiles\". The goal of the program was to provide medical care and services to the region of Basilan as part of a \"Hearts and Minds\" program.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.ait.org.tw/infousa/enus/government/forpolicy/docs/ijpe1104.pdf |title=Improving Lives: Military Humanitarian and Assistance Programs |publisher=[[American Institute in Taiwan]] |date=November 2004 |accessdate=19 January 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111213204848/http://www.ait.org.tw/infousa/enus/government/forpolicy/docs/ijpe1104.pdf |archivedate=13 December 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Operation Enduring Freedom \u2013 Philippines |url=http://www.globalsecurity.org/military/ops/enduring-freedom-philippines.htm |accessdate=19 January 2011 |publisher=GlobalSecurity.org}}</ref> Joint Special Operations Task Force \u2013 Philippines disbanded in June 2014,<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=26 June 2014 |title=US ends Philippines anti-terror force |url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/international/us-ends-philippines-antiterror-force/article6151634.ece |newspaper=The Hindu |agency=Associated Press |accessdate=3 December 2014 |location=Chennai, India}}<br />{{cite news |last=Gomez |first=Jim |date=26 June 2014 |title=US disbanding Philippines elite anti-terror force |url=http://www.philstar.com/headlines/2014/06/26/1339326/us-disbanding-philippines-elite-anti-terror-force |newspaper=The Philippine Star |agency=Associated Press |accessdate=3 December 2014}}</ref> ending a successful 12-year mission.<ref>{{cite news|author1=Gordon Arthur |author2=James Hardy |date=6 October 2014 |title=US, Philippines start 'PHIBLEX' drills as special forces mission draws down |url=http://www.janes.com/article/44106/us-philippines-start-phiblex-drills-as-special-forces-mission-draws-down |newspaper=IHS Janes 360 |accessdate=3 December 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141217100337/http://www.janes.com/article/44106/us-philippines-start-phiblex-drills-as-special-forces-mission-draws-down |archivedate=17 December 2014}}</ref> After JSOTF-P had disbanded, as late as November 2014, American forces continued to operate in the Philippines under the name \"PACOM Augmentation Team\", until 24 February 2015.<ref>{{cite news |last=Trevithick |first=Joseph |date=5 November 2014 |title=Yes, American Commandos Are Still in the Philippines |url=https://medium.com/war-is-boring/yes-american-commandos-are-still-in-the-philippines-f67dea166460 |newspaper=War is Boring |location=Medium.com |accessdate=2 January 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.usni.org/2015/02/27/u-s-officially-ends-special-operations-task-force-in-the-philippines-some-advisors-may-remain|title=U.S. Officially Ends Special Operations Task Force in the Philippines, Some Advisors May Remain |date=27 February 2015|publisher=US Naval Institute}}</ref> By 2018, American operations within the Philippines against terrorist was renamed [[Operation Pacific Eagle]], which involves as many as 300 advisers.<ref>{{cite news |last= |first= |date=19 January 2018 |title=U.S. Military Escalates War Efforts in the Philippines |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-military-escalates-war-efforts-in-the-philippines-1516357801 |url-access=subscription |work=Wall Street Journal |access-date=27 April 2018}}<br />{{cite report |author= |author-link= |authors= |date=2 February 2018 |title=Lead Inspector General for Operation Inherent Resolve and Operation Pacific Eagle-Philippines Quarterly Report to the United States Congress Oct. 1, 2017 \u2013 Dec. 31, 2017 |url=http://www.dodig.mil/In-the-Spotlight/Article/1430714/lead-inspector-general-for-operation-inherent-resolve-and-operation-pacific-eag/ |publisher=Department of Defense Office of Inspector General |page= |docket= |access-date=27 April 2018}}<br />{{cite news |last=Snow |first=Shawn |date=30 December 2017 |title=New in 2018: Conflict hot spots to watch |url=https://www.militarytimes.com/flashpoints/2017/12/30/new-in-2018-conflict-hot-spots-to-watch/ |work=Military Times |access-date=27 April 2018}}<br />{{cite magazine |last=McCormick-Cavanagh |first=Conor |date=30 December 2017 |title=What to Expect in the New American 'War on Terror' in the Philippines |url=http://smallwarsjournal.com/jrnl/art/what-expect-new-american-war-terror-philippines |magazine=Small Wars Journal |access-date=27 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Islamic State of Lanao and the Battle of Marawi===\nWith the rise of the [[Islamic State in Iraq and the Levant]] (ISIL), jihadist offshoots sprung up in [[ISIL territorial claims|regions around the world]], including the Philippines. The [[Maute group]], composed of former [[Moro Islamic Liberation Front]] guerrillas and foreign fighters led by [[Omar Maute]], the alleged founder of a ''Dawlah Islamiya'', declared loyalty to ISIL and began clashing with Philippine security forces and staging [[2016 Davao City bombing|bombings]]. On 23 May 2017, the group attacked the city of [[Marawi]], resulting in the bloody [[Battle of Marawi]] that lasted 5 months. After the decisive battle, remnants of the group were reportedly still recruiting in 2017 and 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2018/09/06/six-killed-in-lanao-del-sur-encounter-between-soldiers-maute-group-remnants/|title=Six killed in Lanao del Sur encounter between soldiers, Maute group remnants|work=Manilla Bulletin|accessdate=22 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/993820/abu-dar-emerges-as-new-maute-group-leader-afp#ixzz5dNuAiB8G|title=Abu Dar emerges as new Maute group leader\u2013AFP|work=Inquirer|accessdate=22 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Operation Pacific Eagle \u2013 Philippines===\nOn 1 September 2017, US Secretary of Defense [[Jim Mattis]] designated Operation Pacific Eagle - Philippines (OPE-P) as a contingency operation to support the Philippine government and the military in their efforts to isolate, degrade, and defeat the affiliates of ISIS (collectively referred to as ISIS-Philippines or ISIS-P) and other terrorist organisations in the Philippines.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.stateoig.gov/system/files/lig_oco_oir1_dec2017_gold.pdf|title=Operation Inherent Resolve Report/Operation Pacific Eagle-Philippines Report to the United States Congress, October 1, 2017-December 31, 2017|publisher=State OIG|date=2 February 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Yemen==\n{{Main|Al-Qaeda insurgency in Yemen|Drone strikes in Yemen}}\nThe United States has also conducted a [[Yemeni al-Qaeda crackdown|series of military strikes on al-Qaeda militants]] in Yemen since the War on Terror began.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ww4report.com/node/8088 |title=Yemen: new air-strikes target al-Qaeda |publisher=World War 4 Report |accessdate=26 March 2011}}</ref> Yemen has a weak central government and a powerful tribal system that leaves large lawless areas open for militant training and operations. Al-Qaeda has a strong presence in the country.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/terrorism-in-the-uk/6898945/Detroit-terror-attack-Yemen-is-the-true-home-of-Al-Qaeda.html |title=Detroit terror attack: Yemen is the true home of Al-Qaeda |date=28 December 2009 |accessdate=26 December 2010 |first=Richard |last=Spencer |work=The Daily Telegraph |location=London}}</ref> On 31 March 2011, AQAP declared the Al-Qaeda Emirate in Yemen after its captured most of [[Abyan Governorate]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/al-qaeda-declares-southern-yemeni-province-an-islamic-emirate-2011-3|title=Al Qaeda Declares Southern Yemeni Province An \"Islamic Emirate\"|work=Business Insider|author=Grace Wyler|date=31 March 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe U.S., in an effort to support Yemeni counter-terrorism efforts, has increased their military aid package to Yemen from less than {{nowrap|$11 million}} in 2006 to more than {{nowrap|$70 million}} in 2009, as well as providing up to {{nowrap|$121 million}} for development over the next three years.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2009/dec/28/al-qaida-us-yemen-attack |work=The Guardian |location=London |title=Al-Qaida: US support for Yemen crackdown led to attack |first=Hugh |last=MacLeod | date=28 December 2009 | accessdate=9 April 2010}}</ref>\n\n==U.S. allies in the Middle East==\n\n===Israel===\n{{Further|Category:Counter-terrorism in Israel}}\nIsrael has been fighting terrorist groups such as [[Hezbollah]], [[Hamas]], and Islamic Jihad, who are all Iran's proxies aimed at Iran's objective to destroy Israel. According to the [[Clarion Project]]: \"Since 1979, Iran has been responsible for countless terrorist plots, directly through regime agents or indirectly through proxies like Hamas and Hezbollah.\"<ref name=\"clarionproject.org\">{{cite web|url=https://www.clarionproject.org/sites/default/files/Iranian-Support-For-Terrorism.pdf|title=Iranian Support for Terrorism |date=20 February 2017|publisher=Clarion Project}}</ref> In 2006, U.S. President [[George W. Bush]] said that Israel's war on terrorist group Hezbollah was part of war on terror.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2006-07-30/lebanon-part-of-war-on-terror-says-bush/1225786|title=Lebanon part of 'war on terror', says Bush|date=30 July 2006|publisher=ABC News |location=Australia}}</ref>\n\n===Saudi Arabia===\n{{Further|List of terrorist incidents in Saudi Arabia}}\nSaudi Arabia witnessed multiple terror attacks from different groups such as Al-Qaeda, whose leader, Osama Bin Laden, declared war on the Saudi government. On 16 June 1996, the [[Khobar Towers bombing]] killed 19 U.S. soldiers. The [[9/11 Commission]] concluded that Hezbollah, likely with the support of the Iranian regime, was the perpetrator of that bombing in Saudi Arabia. It said there are \"signs\" that Al-Qaeda also played a role.<ref name=\"clarionproject.org\" />\n\n==Libya==\n{{Main|2011 military intervention in Libya|Factional violence in Libya (2011\u20132014)|Libyan Civil War (2014\u2013present)|American intervention in Libya (2015\u2013present)}}\nOn 19 March 2011, a multi-state coalition began a military action in Libya, ostensibly to implement [[United Nations Security Council Resolution 1973]]. The [https://www.un.org/News/Press/docs/2011/sc10200.doc.htm United Nations Intent and Voting] was to have \"an immediate ceasefire in Libya, including an end to the current attacks against civilians, which it said might constitute crimes against humanity\" ... \"imposing a ban on all flights in the country's airspace \u2013 a no-fly zone \u2013 and tightened sanctions on the Qadhafi regime and its supporters.\" The resolution was taken in response to events during the [[2011 Libyan Civil War|Libyan Civil War]],<ref name=\"UN-AllNecessaryMeasures\">{{cite web|url=https://www.un.org/News/Press/docs/2011/sc10200.doc.htm|title=Security Council Approves 'No-Fly Zone' over Libya, Authorizing 'All Necessary Measures' To Protect Civilians in Libya, by a Vote of Ten For, None Against, with Five Abstentions|date=17 March 2011|publisher=United Nations|accessdate=19 March 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110319093321/http://www.un.org/News/Press/docs/2011/sc10200.doc.htm|archivedate=19 March 2011|url-status=live}}</ref> and military operations began, with American and British naval forces firing over 110 [[Tomahawk (missile)|Tomahawk cruise missiles]],<ref name=\"al jaz command\">{{cite web|url=http://blogs.aljazeera.net/live/africa/libya-live-blog-march-19 |title=Libya Live Blog \u2013 March&nbsp;19 |date=19 March 2011 |publisher=[[Al Jazeera]] |accessdate=19 March 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5xJ4lwmv0?url=http://blogs.aljazeera.net/live/africa/libya-live-blog-march-19 |archivedate=19 March 2011 |url-status=dead}}</ref> the [[French Air Force]], British [[Royal Air Force]], and [[Royal Canadian Air Force]]<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-africa-12796972|title=Libya: US, UK and France attack Gaddafi forces|date=20 March 2011|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=20 March 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110320053754/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-africa-12796972|archivedate=20 March 2011|url-status=live}}</ref> undertaking [[sorties]] across Libya and a naval [[blockade]] by Coalition forces.<ref name=\"cnn_deployment\">{{cite news|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2011/WORLD/africa/03/19/libya.civil.war|title=French Fighter Jets Deployed over Libya|date=19 March 2011|publisher=CNN|accessdate=19 March 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110322025841/http://edition.cnn.com/2011/WORLD/africa/03/19/libya.civil.war|archivedate=22 March 2011|url-status=live}}</ref> French jets launched air strikes against Libyan Army tanks and vehicles.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.xinhuanet.com/english2010/world/2011-04/29/c_13850700.htm|title=France Uses Unexplosive Bombs in Libya: Spokesman|date=29 April 2011|agency=[[Xinhua News Agency]]|accessdate=29 April 2011}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.nj.com/news/index.ssf/2011/04/nj_voters_back_obamas_decision.html|title=Polled N.J. Voters Back Obama's Decision To Establish No-Fly Zone in Libya|date=8 April 2011|work=[[The Star-Ledger]]|author=Gibson, Ginger|accessdate=29 April 2011}}</ref> The Libyan government response to the campaign was totally ineffectual, with Gaddafi's forces not managing to shoot down a single [[NATO]] plane despite the country possessing 30 heavy [[Surface-to-air missile|SAM]] batteries, 17 medium SAM batteries, 55 light SAM batteries (a total of 400\u2013450 launchers, including 130\u2013150 [[SA-6]] launchers and some [[SA-8]] launchers), and 440\u2013600 short-range air-defense guns.<ref>M. Cherif Bassiouni, \"Libya: From Repression to Revolution\", 13 December 2013, p. 138</ref><ref>[http://csis.org/files/media/csis/pubs/050328_norafrimibal&#x5B;1&#x5D;.pdf \"The North African Military Balance\"], Anthony H. Cordesman, [[Center for Strategic and International Studies]], 29 March 2005, p. 32, p. 36</ref> The official names for the interventions by the coalition members are [[Op\u00e9ration Harmattan]] by France; [[Operation Ellamy]] by the United Kingdom; [[Operation Mobile]] for the Canadian participation and [[Operation Odyssey Dawn]] for the United States.<ref name=\"OdysseyDawn\">{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2011/WORLD/africa/03/19/libya.civil.war/index.html?hpt=T1&iref=BN1|title=Gunfire, Explosions Heard in Tripoli|date=21 March 2011|publisher=CNN |accessdate=20 March 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121103203408/http://www.cnn.com/2011/WORLD/africa/03/19/libya.civil.war/index.html?hpt=T1&iref=BN1 |archivedate=3 November 2012 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nFrom the beginning of the intervention, the initial coalition of [[Belgium]], Canada, [[Denmark]], France, Italy, [[Norway]], [[Qatar]], Spain, UK, and U.S.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eubusiness.com/news-eu/libya-unrest-summit.95v/|title=Qatar, several EU states up for Libya action: diplomat|date=19 March 2011|publisher=EUbusiness.com|accessdate=26 March 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ejpress.org/article/news/germany/49710|title=Paris Summit Talks To Launch Military Action in Libya|date=19 March 2011|publisher=European Jewish Press|accessdate=26 March 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110516041335/http://ejpress.org/article/news/germany/49710|archivedate=16 May 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-africa-12791910|title=Libya: President Obama Gives Gaddafi Ultimatum|date=19 March 2011|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=26 March 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110319080849/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-africa-12791910|archivedate=19 March 2011|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.walesonline.co.uk/news/wales-news/2011/03/20/libya-raf-jets-join-attack-on-air-defense-systems-91466-28369872/|title=Libya: RAF Jets Join Attack on Air Defense Systems|publisher=WalesOnline|accessdate=26 March 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/blog/2011/mar/19/libya-live-blog-ceasefire-nofly|title=Military Action Begins Against Libya|date=19 March 2011|work=[[The Guardian]]|author=Batty, David|accessdate=26 March 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110322195354/http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/blog/2011/mar/19/libya-live-blog-ceasefire-nofly|archivedate=22 March 2011|url-status=live}}</ref> expanded to nineteen states, with newer states mostly enforcing the no-fly zone and naval blockade or providing military logistical assistance. The effort was initially largely led by France and the United Kingdom, with command shared with the United States. NATO took control of the arms embargo on 23 March, named [[Operation Unified Protector]]. An attempt to unify the military leadership of the air campaign (while keeping political and strategic control with a small group), first failed over objections by the French, German, and Turkish governments.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/news/world/deal-puts-nato-at-head-of-libyan-operation/story-e6frg6so-1226027088954|title=Deal Puts NATO at Head of Libyan Operation|date=23 March 2011|website=[[The Australian]]|author=Norington, Brad|accessdate=23 March 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2011/mar/23/libya-no-fly-zone-leadership-squabbles|title=Libya No-Fly Zone Leadership Squabbles Continue Within Nato|date=23 March 2011|work=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=24 March 2011|author1=Traynor, Ian |author2=Watt, Nicholas |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110326232001/http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/2011/mar/23/libya-no-fly-zone-leadership-squabbles|archivedate=26 March 2011|url-status=live}}</ref> On 24 March, NATO agreed to take control of the no-fly zone, while command of targeting ground units remains with coalition forces.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nationalpost.com/arts/books/NATO+reaches+agreement+Libya+command/4498007/story.html |title=NATO reaches agreement on Libya command (Google cached page) |date=24 March 2011 |work=[[National Post]] |author1=Brunnstrom, David |author2=Taylor, Paul |lastauthoramp=yes}}{{Dead link|date=January 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/africa/2011/03/2011324221036894697.html|title=NATO to police Libya no-fly zone|date=24 March 2011|publisher=Al Jazeera}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2011/03/24/nato-command-no-fly-libya-us-combat_n_840408.html|title=NATO Agrees To Take Over Command of Libya No-Fly Zone, U.S. Likely To Remain in Charge of Brunt of Combat|date=24 March 2011|work=[[Huffington Post]]|last2=Werner|first2=Erica|location=Washington D.C.|agency=Associated Press|accessdate=16 January 2012|first1=Robert|last1=Burns}}</ref> The handover occurred on 31 March 2011 at 06:00 [[UTC]] (08:00 local time). NATO flew 26,500 sorties since it took charge of the Libya mission on 31 March 2011.\n\nFighting in Libya ended in late October following the [[death of Muammar Gaddafi]], and NATO stated it would end operations over Libya on 31 October 2011. Libya's [[National Transitional Council|new government]] requested its mission to be extended to the end of the year,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-africa-15459473|title=Libya's Mustafa Abdul Jalil asks Nato to stay longer|date=26 October 2011|publisher=BBC|accessdate=27 October 2011}}</ref> but on 27 October, the Security Council voted to end NATO's mandate for military action on 31 October.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-africa-15481143|title=UN Security Council votes to end Libya operations|date=27 October 2011|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=27 October 2011}}</ref>\n\n[[File:An AV-8B Harrier takes off from the flight deck of USS Wasp (LHD 1) Aug. 8, 2016. (28829655742).jpg|thumb|An [[McDonnell Douglas AV-8B Harrier II|AV-8B Harrier]] takes off from the flight deck of {{USS|Wasp|LHD-1|6}} during [[Military intervention against ISIL#Intervention in Libya|Operation Odyssey Lightning]], 8 August 2016.]]\n\n''NBC News'' reported that in mid-2014, [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant in Libya|ISIS had about 1,000 fighters in Libya]]. Taking advantage of a power vacuum in the center of the country, far from the major cities of Tripoli and Benghazi, ISIS expanded rapidly over the next 18 months. Local militants were joined by jihadists from the rest of North Africa, the Middle East, Europe and the Caucasus. The force absorbed or defeated other Islamist groups inside Libya and the central ISIS leadership in Raqqa, Syria, began urging foreign recruits to head for Libya instead of Syria. ISIS seized control of the coastal city of [[Sirte]] in early 2015 and then began to expand to the east and south. By the beginning of 2016, it had effective control of 120 to 150 miles of coastline and portions of the interior and had reached Eastern Libya's major population center, [[Benghazi]]. In spring 2016, [[United States Africa Command|AFRICOM]] estimated that ISIS had about 5,000 fighters in its stronghold of Sirte.<ref name=\"Did Obama Defeat ISIS in Libya\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/world/did-obama-defeat-isis-libya-n709001|title=Did Obama Defeat ISIS in Libya?|publisher=NBC news|date=28 January 2017}}</ref>\n\nHowever, the indigenous rebel groups who had staked their claims to Libya and turned their weapons on ISIS\u2014with the help of airstrikes by Western forces, including U.S. drones, the Libyan population resented the outsiders who wanted to establish a fundamentalist regime on their soil. Militias loyal to the new Libyan unity government, plus a separate and rival force loyal to a former officer in the Qaddafi regime, [[Battle of Sirte (2016)|launched an assault on ISIS outposts in Sirte]] and the surrounding areas that lasted for months. According to U.S. military estimates, ISIS ranks shrank to somewhere between a few hundred and 2,000 fighters. In August 2016, the [[Military intervention against ISIL#Intervention in Libya|U.S. military began airstrikes]] that, along with continued pressure on the ground from the Libyan militias, pushed the remaining ISIS fighters back into Sirte, In all, U.S. drones and planes hit ISIS nearly 590 times, the Libyan militias reclaimed the city in mid-December.<ref name=\"Did Obama Defeat ISIS in Libya\" /> On 18 January 2017, ABC News reported that two USAF [[Northrop Grumman B-2 Spirit|B-2 bombers]] struck two ISIS camps {{convert|28|mi}} south of Sirte, the airstrikes targeted between 80 and 100 ISIS fighters in multiple camps, an unmanned aircraft also participated in the airstrikes. ''NBC News'' reported that as many as 90 ISIS fighters were killed in the strike, a U.S. defense official said that \"This was the largest remaining ISIS presence in Libya,\" and that \"They have been largely marginalized, but I am hesitant to say they have been eliminated in Libya.\"<ref name=\"Did Obama Defeat ISIS in Libya\" />\n\n==Other military operations==\n===Operation Active Endeavour===\n{{Main|Operation Active Endeavour}}\nOperation Active Endeavour is a [[Navy|naval operation]] of NATO started in October 2001 in response to the 11 September attacks. It operates in the Mediterranean and is designed to prevent the movement of militants or [[weapons of mass destruction]] and to enhance the security of shipping in general.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.nato.int/cps/en/natolive/topics_7932.htm |title=Operation Active Endeavour |publisher=[[NATO]] |date=10 November 2010 |accessdate=19 January 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Fighting in Kashmir===\n{{Main|Kashmir conflict}}\n[[File:Kashmir region 2004.jpg|thumb|upright=0.9|'''Political map:''' the Kashmir region districts]]\nIn a 'Letter to American People' written by [[Osama bin Laden]] in 2002, he stated that one of the reasons he was fighting America is because of its support of India on the Kashmir issue.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.globalsecurity.org/security/library/report/2002/021120-ubl.htm|title=Osama bin Laden \"letter to the American people\"|author=John Pike|publisher=Globalsecurity.org|accessdate=14 September 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2002/nov/24/theobserver|title=Full text: bin Laden's 'letter to America'|work=The Guardian|accessdate=14 September 2014|location=London|date=24 November 2002}}</ref> While on a trip to Delhi in 2002, U.S. Secretary of Defense [[Donald Rumsfeld]] suggested that [[Al-Qaeda]] was active in Kashmir, though he did not have any hard evidence.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/2043800.stm|title=Analysis: Is al-Qaeda in Kashmir?|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=14 September 2014|first=Zaffar|last=Abbas|date=13 June 2002}}</ref><ref name=SMH>{{cite news|url=https://www.smh.com.au/articles/2002/06/13/1023864326179.html|title=Rumsfeld offers US technology to guard Kashmir border|accessdate=14 September 2014|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|date=14 June 2002}}</ref> In 2002, [[The Christian Science Monitor]] published an article claiming that Al-Qaeda and its affiliates were \"thriving\" in [[Pakistan-administered Kashmir]] with the tacit approval of Pakistan's National Intelligence agency [[Inter-Services Intelligence]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.csmonitor.com/2002/0702/p01s02-wosc.html|title=Al Qaeda thriving in Pakistani Kashmir|date=2 July 2002|website=The Christian Science Monitor|accessdate=14 September 2014}}</ref> A team of [[Special Air Service]] and [[Delta Force]] was sent into [[Indian-administered Kashmir]] in 2002 to hunt for Osama bin Laden after reports that he was being sheltered by the Kashmiri militant group [[Harkat-ul-Mujahideen]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/asia/india/1385795/SAS-joins-Kashmir-hunt-for-bin-Laden.html|title=SAS joins Kashmir hunt for bin Laden|date=23 February 2002|work=Telegraph|accessdate=14 September 2014|location=London|first=Michael|last=Smith}}</ref> U.S. officials believed that Al-Qaeda was helping organize a campaign of terror in Kashmir to provoke conflict between India and Pakistan. Fazlur Rehman Khalil, the leader of the Harkat-ul-Mujahideen, signed al-Qaeda's 1998 declaration of holy war, which called on Muslims to attack all Americans and their allies.<ref name=CFRKashmir>{{cite web|url=http://www.cfr.org/publication/9135/|title=Kashmir Militant Extremists|publisher=Council on Foreign Relations|accessdate=14 September 2014|url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070214103922/http://www.cfr.org/publication/9135/|archivedate=14 February 2007}}</ref> Indian sources claimed that In 2006, Al-Qaeda claimed they had established a wing in Kashmir; this worried the Indian government.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2006/07/13/world/asia/13iht-india.2194572.html Al-Qaeda claim of Kashmir link worries India], ''[[The New York Times]]'', 13 July 2006</ref> India also argued that Al-Qaeda has strong ties with the Kashmir militant groups [[Lashkar-e-Taiba]] and [[Jaish-e-Mohammed]] in Pakistan.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/article1857890.ece |title=No Al Qaeda presence in Kashmir: Army |work=The Hindu |date=18 June 2007 |accessdate=2 February 2010 |location=Chennai, India}}</ref> While on a visit to Pakistan in January 2010, U.S. Defense Secretary [[Robert Gates]] stated that Al-Qaeda was seeking to destabilize the region and planning to provoke a nuclear war between India and Pakistan.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dawn.com/wps/wcm/connect/dawn-content-library/dawn/news/world/03-al-qaeda-could-provoke-new-india-pakistan-war-gates-ss-02 |title=Al Qaeda could provoke new India-Pakistan war: Gates |date=20 January 2010 |work=[[Dawn (newspaper)|Dawn]] |accessdate=23 January 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100123140217/http://www.dawn.com/wps/wcm/connect/dawn-content-library/dawn/news/world/03-al-qaeda-could-provoke-new-india-pakistan-war-gates-ss-02 |archivedate=23 January 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2009, a U.S. [[Drone attacks in Pakistan|Drone strike]] reportedly killed [[Ilyas Kashmiri (militant)|Ilyas Kashmiri]], who was the chief of [[Harkat-ul-Jihad al-Islami]], a Kashmiri militant group associated with Al-Qaeda.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dawn.com/wps/wcm/connect/dawn-content-library/dawn/news/world/12-us+drones+killed+two+terrorist+leaders+in+pak--bi-10 |title=US drones killed two terrorist leaders in Pak |accessdate=9 May 2012 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090923225021/http://www.dawn.com/wps/wcm/connect/dawn-content-library/dawn/news/world/12-us+drones+killed+two+terrorist+leaders+in+pak--bi-10 |archivedate=23 September 2009}}, ''[[Dawn (newspaper)|Dawn]]'', 17 September 2009</ref><ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/aponline/2010/01/25/us/AP-US-Chicago-Terrorism-Charges.html Chicago Man Pleads Not Guilty in Terror Cases], ''[[The New York Times]]'', 25 January 2010</ref> Kashmiri was described by [[Bruce Riedel]] as a 'prominent' Al-Qaeda member,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.brookings.edu/opinions/2009/1215_terrorism_riedel.aspx |title=Al Qaeda's American Mole |author=Bruce Riedel |date=15 December 2009 |website=The Brookings Institution |accessdate=14 September 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110924002003/https://www.brookings.edu/opinions/2009/1215_terrorism_riedel.aspx |archivedate=24 September 2011}}</ref> while others described him as the head of military operations for Al-Qaeda.<ref>[http://www.dailytimes.com.pk/default.asp?page=2009%5C10%5C15%5Cstory_15-10-2009_pg1_11 Ilyas Kashmiri alive, lays out future terror strategy], [[Daily Times (Pakistan)]], 15 October 2009 {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110606111931/http://www.dailytimes.com.pk/default.asp?page=2009%5C10%5C15%5Cstory_15-10-2009_pg1_11 |date=6 June 2011}}</ref> [[Waziristan]] had now become the new battlefield for Kashmiri militants, who were now fighting [[NATO]] in support of Al-Qaeda.<ref>[http://www.thenews.com.pk/daily_detail.asp?id=199076 Ilyas Kashmiri had planned to attack COAS], ''[[The News International]]'', 18 September 2009{{Dead link|date=June 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>\nOn 8 July 2012, Al-Badar Mujahideen, a breakaway faction of Kashmir centric terror group Hizbul Mujahideen, on the conclusion of their two-day Shuhada Conference called for a mobilization of resources for continuation of jihad in Kashmir.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.indianexpress.com/news/militants-recruit-in-rawalpindi-for-antiindia-activities/972349/ |title=Militants recruit in Rawalpindi for anti-India activities |date=10 July 2012|work=Indian Express}}</ref>\n\n===American military intervention in Cameroon===\nIn October 2015, the U.S. began deploying 300 soldiers<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2015/oct/14/obama-deployment-us-troops-cameroon-boko-haram |title=Obama to deploy 300 US troops to Cameroon to fight Boko Haram |work=The Guardian |date=14 October 2015 |accessdate=25 October 2015}}</ref> to [[Cameroon]], with the invitation of the Cameroonian government, to support African forces in a non-combat role in their fight against ISIS insurgency in that country. The troops' primary missions will revolve around providing intelligence support to local forces as well as conducting reconnaissance flights.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2015/10/usa-troops-deployed-cameroon-boko-haram-fight-151014212428195.html |title=US troops deployed to Cameroon for Boko Haram fight |publisher=Al Jazeera English |date=14 October 2015 |accessdate=25 October 2015}}</ref>\n\n==International military support==\n{{Main|Participants in Operation Enduring Freedom|Multi-National Force \u2013 Iraq}}\n{{See also|Coalition combat operations in Afghanistan in 2008|Afghan War order of battle 2012}}\n[[File:BritishPatrolHelmand01.jpg|thumb|The United Kingdom is the second largest contributor of troops in [[War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)|Afghanistan]]]]\nThe invasion of Afghanistan is seen to have been the first action of this war, and initially involved forces from the United States, the United Kingdom, and the Afghan [[Northern Alliance]]. Since the initial invasion period, these forces were augmented by troops and aircraft from Australia, Canada, Denmark, France, Italy, Netherlands, New Zealand and Norway amongst others. In 2006, there were about 33,000 troops in Afghanistan.\n\nOn 12 September 2001, less than 24 hours after the 11 September attacks in New York City and Washington, D.C., NATO invoked Article 5 of the [[North Atlantic Treaty]] and declared the attacks to be an attack against all 19 NATO member countries. Australian Prime Minister [[John Howard]] also stated that Australia would invoke the [[ANZUS]] Treaty along similar lines.<ref>{{cite news |publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation |date=14 September 2001 |accessdate=19 January 2011 |url=http://www.abc.net.au/7.30/content/2001/s367069.htm |title=PM speaks on Ansett collapse, Anzus treaty}}</ref>\n\nIn the following months, NATO took a broad range of measures to respond to the threat of terrorism. On 22 November 2002, the member states of the [[Euro-Atlantic Partnership Council]] (EAPC) decided on a Partnership Action Plan against Terrorism, which explicitly states, \"[The] EAPC States are committed to the protection and promotion of fundamental freedoms and human rights, as well as the rule of law, in combating terrorism.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Partnership Action Plan against Terrorism |url=http://pfpdev.ethz.ch/SCORMcontent/72234/scos/93/documents/0.pdf |date=22 November 2002 |accessdate=19 January 2011 |publisher=[[NATO]]}}{{Dead link|date=December 2011}}</ref> NATO started naval operations in the Mediterranean Sea designed to prevent the movement of terrorists or weapons of mass destruction as well as to enhance the security of shipping in general called Operation Active Endeavour.\n\nSupport for the U.S. cooled when America made clear its determination to invade Iraq in late 2002. Even so, many of the \"coalition of the willing\" countries that unconditionally supported the U.S.-led military action have sent troops to Afghanistan, particular neighboring Pakistan, which has disowned its earlier support for the Taliban and contributed tens of thousands of soldiers to the conflict. Pakistan was also engaged in the [[Insurgency in Khyber Pakhtunkhwa]] (a.k.a. Waziristan War or North-West Pakistan War). Supported by U.S. intelligence, Pakistan was attempting to remove the Taliban insurgency and al-Qaeda element from the northern tribal areas.<ref>{{cite news|title=New frontline in the war on terror.}}</ref>\n\n==Terrorist attacks and failed plots since 9/11==\n===Al-Qaeda===\n{{Main|al-Qaeda|Timeline of al-Qaeda attacks}}\nSince 9/11, Al-Qaeda and other affiliated radical Islamist groups have executed attacks in several parts of the world where conflicts are not taking place. Whereas countries like Pakistan have suffered hundreds of attacks killing tens of thousands and displacing much more.\n* The [[2002 Bali bombings]] in Indonesia were committed by various members of [[Jemaah Islamiyah]], an organization linked to Al-Qaeda.\n* The [[2003 Casablanca bombings]] were carried out by [[Salafia Jihadia]], an Al-Qaeda affiliate.\n* After the [[2003 Istanbul bombings]], Turkey charged 74 people with involvement, including Syrian Al-Qaeda member [[Loai al-Saqa]].\n* The [[2004 Madrid train bombings]] in Spain were \"inspired by\" Al-Qaeda, though no direct involvement has been established.\n* The [[7 July 2005 London bombings]] in the United Kingdom were perpetrated by four [[Homegrown terrorism|homegrown terrorists]], one of whom appeared in an edited video with a known Al-Qaeda operative, though the British government denies Al-Qaeda involvement.\n* Al Qaeda claimed responsibility for the [[11 April 2007 Algiers bombings]] in Algeria.\n* The [[2007 Glasgow International Airport attack]] in the United Kingdom was carried out by a pair of bombers whose laptops and suicide notes included videos and speeches referencing Al-Qaeda, though no direct involvement was established.\n* The [[2009 Fort Hood shooting]] in the United States was committed by [[Nidal Malik Hasan]], who had been in communication with [[Anwar al-Awlaki]], though the Department of Defense classifies the shooting as an incidence of workplace violence.\n* Morocco blames Al-Qaeda for the [[2011 Marrakech bombing]], though Al-Qaeda denies involvement.\n* The 2012 [[Toulouse and Montauban shootings]] in France were committed by Mohammed Merah, who reportedly had familial ties to Al-Qaeda, along with a history of petty crime and psychological issues. Merah claimed ties to Al-Qaeda, though French authorities deny any connection.\n* To date, no one has been convicted for the 2012 [[U.S. Consulate attack in Benghazi]] in Libya, and no one has claimed responsibility. Branches of Al-Qaeda, Al-Qaeda affiliates, and individuals \"sympathetic to Al-Qaeda\" are blamed.\n* The gunmen in the 2015 [[Charlie Hebdo shooting|''Charlie Hebdo'' shooting]] in Paris identified themselves as belonging to Al-Qaeda's [[Al-Qaeda in the Arabian Peninsula|branch in Yemen]].\n\nThere may also have been several additional planned attacks that were not successful.\n* [[2004 financial buildings plot]] (The United States and the United Kingdom)\n* [[21 July 2005 London bombings]] (United Kingdom)\n* [[2006 Toronto terrorism plot]] (Canada)\n* [[2006 transatlantic aircraft plot]] involving liquid explosives carried onto commercial airplanes\n* 2006 [[Hudson River bomb plot]] (United States)\n* [[2007 Fort Dix attack plot]] (United States)\n* [[2007 London car bombs]] (United Kingdom)\n* [[2007 John F. Kennedy International Airport attack plot]] (United States)\n* [[2009 Bronx terrorism plot]] (United States)\n* [[2009 New York City Subway and United Kingdom plot]] (The United States and the United Kingdom)\n* 2009 [[Northwest Airlines Flight 253]] bombing plot (United States)\n* [[2010 Stockholm bombings]] (Sweden)\n* [[2010 Times Square car bombing attempt]] (United States)\n* [[2010 cargo plane bomb plot]] (United States)\n* [[2010 Portland car bomb plot]] (United States)\n* [[2011 Manhattan terrorism plot]] (United States)\n* [[2013 VIA Rail Canada terrorism plot]] (Canada)\n\n===The Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant (ISIL)===\n{{Main|Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant|List of terrorist incidents linked to ISIL}}\n* 2013 [[Reyhanl\u0131 bombings]] in Turkey that led to 52 deaths and the injury of 140 people.\n* 2014 [[2014 shootings at Parliament Hill, Ottawa|Canadian parliament shootings]], an ISIL-inspired attack on Canada's Parliament, resulting in the death of a Canadian soldier, as well as that of the perpetrator.\n* 2015 [[Porte de Vincennes siege]] perpetrated by [[Amedy Coulibaly]] in Paris, which led to four deaths and the injury of nine others.\n* [[2015 Corinthia Hotel attack]] on 27 January in Libya that resulted in 10 deaths.\n* [[2015 Sana'a mosque bombings]] on 20 March that led to the death of 142 and injury of 351 people.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-yemen-attack-bomb/suicide-bombers-kill-137-in-yemen-mosque-attacks-idUSKBN0MG11J20150320 |title=Suicide bombers kill 137 in Yemen mosque attacks |first=Mohammed |last=Ghobari |first2=Mohammed |last2=Mukhashaf |date=20 March 2015 |access-date=7 June 2019 |work=[[Reuters]] |editor-first=Sami |editor-last=Aboudi |editor2-first=Omar |editor2-last=Fahmy |editor3-first=Rania |editor3-last=El Gamal |editor4-first=Peter |editor4-last=Graff |editor5-first=John |editor5-last=Stonestreet}}</ref>\n* 2015 [[Curtis Culwell Center attack]] on 3 May 2015 that resulted in the injury of one [[security officer]].\n* [[November 2015 Paris attacks]] on the 13th that left at least 137 dead and injured at least 352 civilians caused France to be put under a state of emergency, close its borders and deploy three French contingency plans.<ref>{{cite web|title=Paris attacks: Suspect on the run as terror raids end in failure&nbsp;\u2014 latest news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/france/11997820/Paris-France-terror-attacks-isil-suspects-Syria-Raqqa-boming-arrests-live.html|website=Telegraph |accessdate=16 November 2015}}</ref> Islamic State claimed responsibility for the attacks,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.france24.com/fr/urgent/20151114-lorganisation-etat-islamique-revendique-attentats-paris |title=L'organisation \u00c9tat islamique revendique les attentats de Paris |date=14 November 2015 |publisher=France 24 |language=French |access-date=14 November 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151114163337/http://www.france24.com/fr/urgent/20151114-lorganisation-etat-islamique-revendique-attentats-paris |archive-date=14 November 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref> with French President [[Fran\u00e7ois Hollande]] later stated the attacks were carried out \"by the Islamic state with internal help\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-34820016|title=Paris attacks: Hollande blames Islamic State for 'act of war'|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=14 November 2015}}</ref>\n* [[2015 San Bernardino attack]] on 2 December 2015, two gunmen attacked a county building in San Bernardino, California killing 16 people and injuring 24 others.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/12/06/world/middleeast/islamic-state-san-bernardino-massacre.html|title=Islamic State Says 'Soldiers of Caliphate' Attacked in San Bernardino|first=Rukmini|last=Callimachi|date=5 December 2015|work=New York Times}}</ref>\n* [[2016 Brussels bombing]] on 22 March 2016 two bombing attacks, first at [[Brussels Airport]] and the second at the [[Maalbeek/Maelbeek metro station]], killed 35 people and injured more than 300.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/mar/22/brussels-airport-explosions-heard |title=Islamic State claims attacks at Brussels airport and metro station |first=Jennifer |last=Rankin |first2=Jon |last2=Henley |date=22 March 2016 |access-date=7 June 2019 |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |publisher=[[Guardian News & Media Limited]]}}</ref>\n* [[2016 Orlando nightclub shooting]] on 12 June 2016 a gunman opened fire at the Pulse nightclub in Orlando, Florida killing 50 people and wounding 53 others. It was the second worst mass shooting in U.S. history.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/mass-shooting-at-orlando-nightclub-pulse-isis-takes-responsibility/|title=ISIS claims responsibility for Orlando mass shooting|publisher=CBS News|date=12 June 2016}}</ref>\n* As well as a thwarted 2014 [[2014 Australian counter-terrorism raids|mass-beheading plot]] in Australia.\n\n==Post 9/11 events inside the United States==\n<!--Maybe some other title is more appropriate-->\n{{Main|Patriot Act}}\n{{further|Detentions following the September 11 attacks|Aftermath of the September 11 attacks|NSA warrantless surveillance (2001\u20132007)}}\n{{See also|Global surveillance disclosures (1970\u20132013)#2000s|Global surveillance disclosures (2013\u2013present)}}\n[[File:Liberty.jpg|thumb|upright|A [[U.S. Immigration and Customs Enforcement]] helicopter patrols the airspace over New York City]]\nIn addition to military efforts abroad, in the aftermath of 9/11, the Bush Administration increased domestic efforts to prevent future attacks. Various government bureaucracies that handled security and military functions were reorganized. A new cabinet-level agency called the [[United States Department of Homeland Security]] was created in November 2002 to lead and coordinate the largest reorganization of the U.S. federal government since the consolidation of the armed forces into the Department of Defense.{{Citation needed|date=May 2010}}\n\nThe Justice Department launched the [[National Security Entry-Exit Registration System]] for certain male non-citizens in the U.S., requiring them to register in person at offices of the [[Immigration and Naturalization Service]].\n\nThe USA PATRIOT Act of October 2001 dramatically reduces restrictions on law enforcement agencies' ability to search telephone, e-mail communications, medical, financial, and other records; eases restrictions on foreign intelligence gathering within the United States; expands the [[Secretary of the Treasury]]'s authority to regulate financial transactions, particularly those involving foreign individuals and entities; and broadens the discretion of law enforcement and immigration authorities in detaining and deporting immigrants suspected of terrorism-related acts. The act also expanded the definition of terrorism to include domestic terrorism, thus enlarging the number of activities to which the USA PATRIOT Act's expanded law enforcement powers could be applied. A new [[Terrorist Finance Tracking Program]] monitored the movements of terrorists' financial resources (discontinued after being revealed by ''[[The New York Times]]''). Global telecommunication usage, including those with no links to terrorism,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2013/oct/10/double-danger-nsa-surveillance |title=The double danger of the NSA's 'collect it all' policy on surveillance |author=Rachel Levinson-Waldman |work=The Guardian |accessdate=27 February 2014}}</ref> is being collected and monitored through the [[NSA electronic surveillance program]]. The Patriot Act is still in effect.\n\nPolitical interest groups have stated that these laws remove important restrictions on governmental authority, and are a dangerous encroachment on civil liberties, possible [[Constitutionality|unconstitutional]] violations of the [[Fourth Amendment to the United States Constitution|Fourth Amendment]]. On 30 July 2003, the [[American Civil Liberties Union]] (ACLU) filed the first legal challenge against Section 215 of the Patriot Act, claiming that it allows the [[FBI]] to violate a citizen's [[First Amendment to the United States Constitution|First Amendment]] rights, Fourth Amendment rights, and right to [[due process]], by granting the government the right to search a person's business, bookstore, and library records in a terrorist investigation, without disclosing to the individual that records were being searched.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ala.org/ala/alonline/currentnews/newsarchive/2003/august2003/firstpatriot.cfm |title=American Libraries \u2013 First Patriot Act Challenge Filed by ACLU |publisher=ALA |date=4 August 2003 |accessdate=26 March 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120122043434/http://www.ala.org/ala/alonline/currentnews/newsarchive/2003/august2003/firstpatriot.cfm |archivedate=22 January 2012}}</ref> Also, governing bodies in many communities have passed symbolic resolutions against the act.\n[[File:John Walker Lindh Custody.jpg|thumb|upright|[[John Walker Lindh]] was captured as an enemy combatant during the United States' [[War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)|2001 invasion of Afghanistan]]]]\n\nIn a speech on 9 June 2005, Bush said that the USA PATRIOT Act had been used to bring charges against more than 400 suspects, more than half of whom had been convicted. Meanwhile, the ACLU quoted Justice Department figures showing that 7,000 people have complained of abuse of the Act.\n\nThe Defense Advanced Research Projects Agency ([[DARPA]]) began an initiative in early 2002 with the creation of the [[Total Information Awareness]] program, designed to promote information technologies that could be used in counter-terrorism. This program, facing criticism, has since been defunded by Congress.\n\nBy 2003, 12 major conventions and protocols were designed to combat terrorism. These were adopted and ratified by many states. These conventions require states to co-operate on principal issues regarding unlawful seizure of aircraft, the physical protection of nuclear materials, and the freezing of assets of militant networks.<ref>Cindy C Combs (2003), ''Terrorism in the Twenty First Century'', (3rd Edition, New Jersey: Pearsons Educ. Inc.)</ref>\n\nIn 2005, the UN Security Council adopted [[United Nations Security Council Resolution 1624|Resolution 1624]] concerning incitement to commit acts of terrorism and the obligations of countries to comply with international human rights laws.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.un.org/sc/ctc/ |title=UN Security Council Counter-Terrorism Committee |publisher=United Nations |accessdate=26 March 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100611145715/http://www.un.org/sc/ctc/ |archivedate=11 June 2010}}</ref> Although both resolutions require mandatory annual reports on counter-terrorism activities by adopting nations, the United States and Israel have both declined to submit reports. In the same year, the [[United States Department of Defense]] and the [[Chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff]] issued a planning document, by the name \"National Military Strategic Plan for the War on Terrorism\", which stated that it constituted the \"comprehensive military plan to prosecute the Global War on Terror for the [[Military of the United States|Armed Forces of the United States]]...including the findings and recommendations of the [[9/11 Commission]] and a rigorous examination with the Department of Defense\".\n\nOn 9 January 2007, the House of Representatives passed a bill, by a vote of 299\u2013128, enacting many of the recommendations of the 9/11 Commission The bill passed in the U.S. Senate,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.senate.gov/legislative/LIS/roll_call_lists/roll_call_vote_cfm.cfm?congress=110&session=1&vote=00073|title=U.S. Senate: Roll Call Vote|date=27 January 2015|website=senate.gov|accessdate=25 June 2015}}</ref> by a vote of 60\u201338, on 13 March 2007 and it was signed into law on 3 August 2007 by President Bush. It became Public Law 110\u201353. In July 2012, U.S. Senate passed a resolution urging that the [[Haqqani Network]] be designated a [[U.S. State Department list of Foreign Terrorist Organizations|foreign terrorist organization]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.indianexpress.com/news/us-cong-votes-for-designating-haqqani-network-as-terror-group/980665/|title=US Cong votes for designating Haqqani network as terror group |date=28 July 2012|work=Indian Express}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Office of Strategic Influence]] was secretly created after 9/11 for the purpose of coordinating propaganda efforts but was closed soon after being discovered. The Bush administration implemented the [[Continuity of Operations Plan]] (or Continuity of Government) to ensure that U.S. government would be able to continue in catastrophic circumstances.\n\nSince 9/11, extremists made various attempts to attack the United States, with varying levels of organization and skill. For example, vigilant passengers aboard a transatlantic flight prevented [[Richard Reid (shoe bomber)|Richard Reid]], in 2001, and [[Umar Farouk Abdulmutallab]], in 2009, from detonating an explosive device.\n\nOther terrorist plots have been stopped by federal agencies using new legal powers and investigative tools, sometimes in cooperation with foreign governments.{{citation needed|date=November 2015}}\n\nSuch thwarted attacks include:\n* The [[2001 shoe bomb plot]]\n* A plan to crash airplanes into the [[U.S. Bank Tower (Los Angeles)|U.S. Bank Tower]] (aka Library Tower) in Los Angeles\n* The 2003 plot by [[Iyman Faris]] to blow up the [[Brooklyn Bridge]] in New York City\n* The [[2004 Financial buildings plot]], which targeted the [[International Monetary Fund]] and [[World Bank]] buildings in Washington, D.C., the [[New York Stock Exchange]] and other financial institutions\n* The 2004 [[Columbus Shopping Mall Bombing Plot]]\n* The [[2006 Sears Tower plot]]\n* The [[2007 Fort Dix attack plot]]\n* The [[2007 John F. Kennedy International Airport attack plot]]\n* The [[Najibullah Zazi|New York Subway Bombing Plot]] and [[2010 Times Square car bombing attempt]]\n\nThe Obama administration has promised the closing of the [[Guantanamo Bay detention camp]], increased the number of troops in [[War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)|Afghanistan]], and promised the withdrawal of its forces from [[War in Iraq|Iraq]].\n\n==Transnational actions==\n===\"Extraordinary rendition\"===\n[[File:CIA illegal flights.svg|thumb|Alleged \"extraordinary rendition\" illegal flights of the [[CIA]], as reported by ''[[Rzeczpospolita (newspaper)|Rzeczpospolita]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rp.pl/artykul/292283.html |title=Politycy nie pozwolili \u015bledczym tropi\u0107 lot\u00f3w CIA \u2013 Rzeczpospolita |language=pl |work=Rzeczpospolita |date=17 April 2009 |accessdate=17 July 2010}}</ref>]]\n[[File:CIA Secret Prisons.svg|thumb|CIA's Extraordinary Rendition and Detention Program \u2013 countries involved in the Program, according to the 2013 [[Open Society Foundation]]'s report on [[torture]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.transcend.org/tms/2013/02/the-latin-american-exception-how-a-washington-global-torture-gulag-was-turned-into-the-only-gulag-free-zone-on-earth/|title=TRANSCEND MEDIA SERVICE|publisher=TRANSCEND Media Service}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.opensocietyfoundations.org/projects/globalizing-torture|title=CIA Secret Detention and Torture|publisher=opensocietyfoundations.org|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130220112418/http://www.opensocietyfoundations.org/projects/globalizing-torture|archivedate=20 February 2013}}</ref>]]\nAfter the 11 September attacks, the United States government commenced a program of illegal \"[[extraordinary rendition]],\" sometimes referred to as \"irregular rendition\" or \"forced rendition,\" the government-sponsored [[kidnapping|abduction]] and [[extrajudicial]] transfer of a person from one country to transferee countries, with the consent of transferee countries.<ref name=\"54 countries\">{{cite news |author=Max Fisher |title=A staggering map of the 54 countries that reportedly participated in the CIA's rendition program|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/worldviews/wp/2013/02/05/a-staggering-map-of-the-54-countries-that-reportedly-participated-in-the-cias-rendition-program/ |work=[[The Washington Post]] |date=5 February 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2013/may/22/us-extraordinary-rendition-programme|title=New light shed on US government's extraordinary rendition programme|first1=Ian|last1=Cobain|first2=James|last2=Ball|date=22 May 2013|work=The Guardian}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2016/mar/28/cia-photographed-naked-detainees|title=CIA photographed detainees naked before sending them to be tortured|first=Spencer |last=Ackerman|date=28 March 2016|work=The Guardian}}</ref> The aim of extraordinary rendition is often conducting [[torture]] on the detainee that would be difficult to conduct in the U.S. legal environment, a practice known as [[torture by proxy]].  Starting in 2002, U.S. government rendered hundreds of [[illegal combatant]]s for U.S. detention, and transported detainees to U.S. controlled sites as part of an extensive interrogation program that included [[enhanced interrogation|torture]].<ref>Bush administration increased renditions\n* {{cite news |author=Jane Mayer |title=Outsourcing torture |url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2005/02/14/outsourcing-torture |work=[[The New Yorker]] |date=14 February 2005 |accessdate=26 October 2014}}\n* Greenwald, Glenn. [http://www.salon.com/news/opinion/glenn_greenwald/2008/12/15/rumsfeld Senate Report Links Bush to Detainee Homicides; Media Yawns], Salon.com, 15 December 2008.\n* [http://pubrecord.org/torture/292/senate-panels-report-links-detainees-murders-to-bushs-torture-policy/ \"Senate Panel's Report Links Detainees\u2019 Murders to Bush's Torture Policy\"] ''The Public Record'', 30 April 2009.\n* Barnes, Greg and Miller, Julian. [https://articles.latimes.com/2008/dec/12/nation/na-interrogate-abuse12 \"Senate Report Says Rumsfeld to Blame for Detainee Abuse\"] ''Los Angeles Times'', 12 September 2008.</ref> Extraordinary rendition continued under the [[Barack Obama|Obama]] administration; with targets being interrogated and subsequently taken to the US for trial.<ref>Obama administration renditions\n* {{cite web |url=http://www.slate.com/blogs/the_slatest/2015/06/16/senate_votes_to_ban_torture_will_it_stick_this_time.html |title=Senate votes to ban torture: Will It Stick This Time? |newspaper=Slate |date=16 June 2015 |author=Joshua Keeting |accessdate=16 June 2015}}\n* {{cite news |author=Craig Whitlock |title=Renditions continue under Obama, despite due-process concerns |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/renditions-continue-under-obama-despite-due-process-concerns/2013/01/01/4e593aa0-5102-11e2-984e-f1de82a7c98a_story.html |work=The Washington Post |date=1 January 2013 |accessdate=26 October 2014}}\n* {{cite news |author=Cora Currier |author2=Suevon Lee |title=The Secret Prison |url=http://www.slate.com/articles/news_and_politics/propublica/2012/07/extraordinary_rendition_proxy_detention_and_gitmo_during_the_obama_administration.html |work=[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]] |date=26 July 2012 |accessdate=26 October 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe [[United Nations]] considers one nation abducting the citizens of another a [[crime against humanity]].<ref name=\"MyUser_The_Washington_Post_July_26_2015c\">{{cite web |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/worldviews/wp/2014/11/20/torture-kidnapping-and-gulags-north-koreas-alleged-crimes-against-humanity/ |title=Torture, kidnapping and gulags: North Korea's alleged crimes against humanity |newspaper=The Washington Post |date= 20 November 2014  |author=Adam Taylor |accessdate= 26 July 2015}}</ref> In July 2014 the [[European Court of Human Rights]] condemned the [[government of Poland]] for participating in CIA extraordinary rendition, ordering Poland to pay restitution to men who had been abducted, taken to a CIA [[black site]] in Poland, and tortured.<ref name=\"European Court of Human Rights\">{{cite news |author= AFP |title=European court condemns Poland over secret CIA torture prisons|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/poland/10989149/European-court-condemns-Poland-over-secret-CIA-torture-prisons.html |work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |date=24 July 2014 |accessdate=26 October 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author=Dan Bilesfsky |title=Court Censures Poland Over C.I.A. Renditions|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/07/25/world/europe/europe-poland-cia-black-site-extraordinary-rendition.html |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=24 July 2014 |accessdate=26 October 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"MyUser_Reuters.com_February_24_2015c\">{{cite web |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2015/02/17/us-usa-cia-torture-poland-idUSKBN0LL1TP20150217 |title=European court rejects Polish appeal in CIA jail case |publisher=Reuters |date= 17 February 2015 |author=Christian Lowe |accessdate= 24 February 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Rendition to \"Black Sites\"===\nIn 2005, ''The Washington Post'' and [[Human Rights Watch]] (HRW) published revelations concerning kidnapping of detainees by the [[U.S. Central Intelligence Agency]] and their transport to \"[[black site]]s,\" covert prisons operated by the CIA whose existence is denied by the US government. The [[European Parliament]] published a report connecting use of such secret detention Black Sites for detainees kidnapped as part of extraordinary rendition (''[[Extraordinary rendition#The European Parliament's 14 February 2007 report|See below]]''). Although some Black Sites have been known to exist inside [[European Union]] states, these detention centers violate the [[European Convention on Human Rights]] (ECHR) and the [[United Nations Convention Against Torture|UN Convention Against Torture]], treaties that all EU member states are bound to follow.<ref>{{cite news |title=Europeans Probe Secret CIA Flights |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2005/11/16/AR2005111602198.html |accessdate=18 December 2005 |work=The Washington Post |first=Craig |last=Whitlock |date=17 November 2005}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title= EU to look into 'secret US jails' |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/4403166.stm |accessdate=18 December 2005 |publisher=BBC News |date=3 November 2005}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=U.S. Faces Scrutiny Over Secret Prisons |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2005/11/03/AR2005110300422.html |accessdate=18 December 2005 |work=The Washington Post |first=Craig |last=Whitlock |date=4 November 2005}}</ref> The U.S. had ratified the United Nations Convention Against Torture in 1994.<ref>United Nations Treaty Collection, [https://treaties.un.org/Pages/ViewDetails.aspx?src=TREATY&mtdsg_no=IV-9&chapter=4&clang=_en Convention against Torture and Other Cruel, Inhuman or Degrading Treatment or Punishment]</ref>\n\nAccording to [[ABC News]] two such facilities, in countries mentioned by Human Rights Watch, have been closed following the recent publicity with the CIA relocating the detainees. Almost all of these detainees were tortured as part of the \"[[enhanced interrogation techniques]]\" of the CIA.<ref name=\"AbcNews051205\">{{cite news |title=Exclusive: Sources Tell ABC News Top Al Qaeda Figures Held in Secret CIA Prisons |url=https://abcnews.go.com/WNT/Investigation/story?id=1375123 |accessdate=18 December 2005 |publisher=ABC News |date=5 December 2005}}</ref>\n\n====Criticism of American Media's Withholding of Coverage====\nMajor American newspapers, such as \"[[The Washington Post]],\" have been criticized for deliberately withholding publication of articles reporting locations of Black Sites. The Post defended its decision to suppress this news on the ground that such revelations \"could open the [[U.S. government]] to legal challenges, particularly in foreign courts, and increase the risk of political condemnation at home and abroad.\" However, according to [[Fairness and Accuracy In Reporting]] \"the possibility that illegal, unpopular government actions might be disrupted is not a consequence to be feared, however\u2014it's the whole point of the [[First Amendment to the United States Constitution|U.S. First Amendment]]. ... Without the basic fact of where these prisons are, it's difficult if not impossible for 'legal challenges' or 'political condemnation' to force them to close.\" FAIR argued that the damage done to the global reputation of the United States by the continued existence of black-site prisons was more dangerous than any threat caused by the exposure of their locations.<ref name=\"FAIR 2005\">{{cite web |title=The Consequences of Covering Up |url=http://www.fair.org/index.php?page=2715 |accessdate=18 December 2005}}</ref>\n\n<blockquote>The complex at Stare Kiejkuty, a Soviet-era compound once used by German intelligence in World War II, is best known as having been the only Russian intelligence training school to operate outside the Soviet Union. Its prominence in the Soviet era suggests that it may have been the facility first identified\u2014but never named\u2014when the Washington Post's Dana Priest revealed the existence of the CIA's secret prison network in November 2005.<ref>{{cite web |title=Soviet-era compound in northern Poland was site of secret CIA interrogation, detentions |url=http://www.rawstory.com/news/2007/Sovietera_compound_in_Poland_was_site_0307.html}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nThe journalists who exposed this provided their sources and this information and documents were provided to ''The Washington Post'' in 2005. In addition, they also identified such Black Sites are concealed:\n\n{{quote|Former European and US intelligence officials indicate that the secret prisons across the European Union, first identified by the Washington Post, are likely not permanent locations, making them difficult to identify and locate.\n\nWhat some believe was a network of secret prisons was most probably a series of facilities used temporarily by the United States when needed, officials say. Interim \"black sites\"\u2014secret facilities used for covert activities\u2014can be as small as a room in a government building, which only becomes a black site when a prisoner is brought in for short-term detainment and interrogation.}}\n\nThe journalists went on to explain that \"Such a site, sources say, would have to be near an airport.\" The airport in question is the [[Szczytno-Szymany International Airport]].\n\nIn response to these allegations, former Polish intelligence chief, [[Zbigniew Siemiatkowski]], embarked on a media blitz and claimed that the allegations were \"... part of the domestic political battle in the US over who is to succeed current Republican President George W Bush,\" according to the German news agency Deutsche Presse Agentur.<ref>{{cite web |title=Former Polish intelligence chief who says report on CIA detention site part of US domestic battle admitted CIA had access to facility |work=The Raw Story |url=http://rawstory.com/news/2007/Former_Polish_intelligence_chief_who_says_0308.html}}</ref>\n\n==== Prison ships ====\nThe United States has also been accused of operating \"[[Prison ship|floating prisons]]\" to house and transport those arrested in its [[war on terror#US objectives|''War on Terror'']], according to human rights lawyers. They have claimed that the US has tried to conceal the numbers and whereabouts of detainees. Although no credible information to support these assertions has ever come to light, the alleged justification for prison ships is primarily to remove the ability for jihadists to target a fixed location to facilitate the escape of high value targets, commanders, operations chiefs etc.<ref>{{cite news|author1=Duncan Campbell |author2=Richard Norton-Taylor |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2008/jun/02/usa.humanrights |title=US accused of holding terror suspects on prison ships |work=The Guardian |location=London |date=2 June 2008|accessdate=17 July 2010}}</ref>\n\n=== Guantanamo Bay detention camp ===\n[[File:Camp x-ray detainees.jpg|thumb|Detainees upon arrival at [[Camp X-Ray (Guantanamo)|Camp X-Ray]], January 2002]]\n\nThe U.S. government set up the [[Guantanamo Bay detention camp]] in 2002, a United States [[military prison]] located in [[Guantanamo Bay Naval Base]].<ref name=\"Independent060429\">[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/guantanamo-bay-prisoners-plant-seeds-of-hope-in-secret-garden-476011.html Guantanamo Bay prisoners plant seeds of hope in secret garden] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150925171350/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/guantanamo-bay-prisoners-plant-seeds-of-hope-in-secret-garden-476011.html |date=25 September 2015}}, ''[[The Independent]]'', 29 April 2006</ref> President [[George W. Bush|Bush]] declared that the [[Geneva Convention]], a treaty ratified by the U.S. and therefore among the highest law of the land, which protects [[prisoner of war|prisoners of war]], would not apply to Taliban and al Qaida detainees captured in Afghanistan.<ref>James P. Pfiffner, \"Power Play: The Bush Presidency and the Constitution,\" (Washington, DC: [[Brookings Institution]] Press, 2008), p. 146\u2013149</ref> Since inmates were [[indefinite detention without trial|detained indefinitely without trial]] and several detainees have allegedly been [[torture]]d, this camp is considered to be a major breach of human rights by [[Amnesty International]].<ref name=\"withouttrial\">[http://www.amnestyusa.org/our-work/issues/security-and-human-rights/guantanamo Guantanamo and Illegal Detention] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161015152944/http://www.amnestyusa.org/our-work/issues/security-and-human-rights/guantanamo |date=15 October 2016}}, Amnesty International. Retrieved 3 November 2016</ref> The detention camp was set up by the U.S. government on Guantanamo Bay since the military base is arguably not legally domestic US territory and thus was a \"legal black hole.\"<ref>[[The Independent]], 9 May 2010, \"[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/exclusive-caught-in-americas-legal-black-hole-2047307.html Exclusive: Caught in America's Legal Black Hole]\"</ref><ref>Steyn, Johan, \"[https://www.jstor.org/stable/3663134?seq=1#page_scan_tab_contents Guantanamo Bay: The Legal Black Hole]\" ''The International and Comparative Law Quarterly'', vol. 53, no. 1, 2004, pp. 1\u201315. JSTOR</ref> Most prisoners of Guantanamo were eventually freed without ever being charged with any crime, and were transferred to other countries.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.faz.net/aktuell/politik/ausland/machtwechsel-in-amerika-zehn-guantanamo-gefangene-nach-oman-ueberstellt-14667163.html|title=Machtwechsel in Amerika: Zehn Guant\u00e1namo-Gefangene nach Oman \u00fcberstellt|date=16 January 2017|via=Frankfurter Allgemeine Zeitung}}</ref>\n\n==Casualties==\n{{Main|Casualties of the Iraq War|Coalition casualties in Afghanistan}}\nAccording to Joshua Goldstein, an [[international relations]] professor at the [[American University]], The Global War on Terror has seen fewer war deaths than any other decade in the past century.<ref>Goldstein, Joshua S. [https://foreignpolicy.com/articles/2011/08/15/think_again_war \"Think Again: War\"]. ''Foreign Policy Magazine'', 15 August 2011.</ref>\n\nThere is no widely agreed on figure for the number of people that have been killed so far in the War on Terror as it has been defined by the Bush Administration to include the war in Afghanistan, the war in Iraq, and operations elsewhere. The [[International Physicians for the Prevention of Nuclear War]] and the Physicians for Social Responsibility and Physicians for Global Survival give total estimates ranging from {{nowrap|1.3 million}} to {{nowrap|2 million}} casualties.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitaljournal.com/news/world/study-1-3-million-killed-in-usa-war-on-terror/article/429180|title=Doctors' group says 1.3 million killed in U.S. 'War on Terror'|date=25 March 2015|work=Digital Journal}}</ref> Another study from 2018 by Brown University's [[Watson Institute for International and Public Affairs]] puts the total number of casualties of the War on Terror in Iraq, Afghanistan and Pakistan between 480,000 and 507,000.<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=9 November 2018 |title=US 'war on terror' has killed over half a million people: study|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2018/11/wars-terror-killed-million-people-study-181109080620011.html|newspaper=[[Al Jazeera]] |access-date=12 November 2018}}</ref> A 2019 Brown University study places the number of direct deaths caused by the War on Terror at over 800,000 when Syria and Yemen are included, with the toll rising to 3.1 million or more once indirect deaths are taken into account.<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=November 15, 2019 |title=Analysis Finds U.S.-Led Wars Since 9/11 Killed 801,000 at a Cost of $6.4 Trillion|url=https://www.democracynow.org/2019/11/15/headlines/analysis_finds_us_led_wars_since_9_11_killed_801_000_at_a_cost_of_64_trillion|work=[[Democracy Now!]] |location= |access-date=November 16, 2019}}</ref> Some estimates for regional conflicts include the following:\n[[File:CollateralMurder.ogv|thumb|Footage of leaked [[July 12, 2007 Baghdad airstrike|Apache gunship strike]] in Baghdad, July 2007]]\n\n* Iraq: 62,570 to 1,124,000\n:* [[Iraq Body Count project]] documented 110,937\u2013121,227 civilian deaths from violence from March 2003 to December 2012.<ref name=iraqbodycountlogs>[[Staff writer]] (23 October 2010). [http://www.iraqbodycount.org/analysis/numbers/warlogs \"Iraq War Logs: What the Numbers Reveal\"]. [[Iraq Body Count]]. Retrieved 20 November 2010.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iraqbodycount.org/analysis/numbers/2011/ |title=Civilian deaths from violence in 2003\u20132011 |publisher=Iraq Body Count |date=2 January 2012 |accessdate=10 October 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iraqbodycount.org/analysis/numbers/2012/ |title=Civilian deaths from violence in 2012 |publisher=Iraq Body Count |date=1 January 2013}}</ref>\n:* 110,600 deaths in total according to the [[Associated Press]] from March 2003 to April 2009.<ref>Associated Press, 14 October 2009</ref>\n:* 151,000 deaths in total according to the [[Iraq Family Health Survey]].<ref>{{Cite journal|title=Iraq Family Health Survey|journal=New England Journal of Medicine|volume=358|issue=5 |pages=484\u2013493|doi=10.1056/NEJMsa0707782|pmid=18184950|year=2008|author1=Iraq Family Health Survey Study Group|last2=Alkhuzai|first2=A. H|last3=Ahmad|first3=I. J|last4=Hweel|first4=M. J|last5=Ismail|first5=T. W|last6=Hasan|first6=H. H|last7=Younis|first7=A. R|last8=Shawani|first8=O|last9=Al-Jaf|first9=V. M|last10=Al-Alak|first10=M. M|last11=Rasheed|first11=L. H|last12=Hamid|first12=S. M|last13=Al-Gasseer|first13=N|last14=Majeed|first14=F. A|last15=Al Awqati|first15=N. A|last16=Ali|first16=M. M|last17=Boerma|first17=J. T|last18=Mathers |first18=C}}</ref>\n:* [[ORB survey of Iraq War casualties|Opinion Research Business (ORB) poll]] conducted 12\u201319 August 2007 estimated 1,033,000 violent deaths due to the Iraq War. The range given was 946,000 to 1,120,000 deaths. A nationally representative sample of approximately 2,000 Iraqi adults answered whether any members of their household (living under their roof) were killed due to the Iraq War. 22% of the respondents had lost one or more household members. ORB reported that \"48% died from a gunshot wound, 20% from the impact of a car bomb, 9% from aerial bombardment, 6% as a result of an accident and 6% from another blast/ordnance.\"<ref name=ORB>{{cite web |url=http://www.opinion.co.uk/Newsroom_details.aspx?NewsId=78 |title=More than 1,000,000 Iraqis murdered |accessdate=2 October 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071002205022/http://www.opinion.co.uk/Newsroom_details.aspx?NewsId=78 |archivedate=2 October 2007}}. September 2007. Opinion Research Business. PDF report: [http://www.opinion.co.uk/Documents/TABLES.pdf Opinion.co.uk]  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070925235801/http://www.opinion.co.uk/Documents/TABLES.pdf |date=25 September 2007}}</ref><ref name=ORB2>{{cite web|url=http://www.commondreams.org/archive/2007/09/14/3839/|title=Poll: Civilian Death Toll in Iraq May Top 1 Million|website=Common Dreams|accessdate=14 September 2014}}</ref><ref name=ORB3>{{cite web|url=http://www.commondreams.org/archive/2007/09/16/3879/|title=Greenspan Admits Iraq was About Oil, As Deaths Put at 1.2 Million|website=Common Dreams|accessdate=14 September 2014}}</ref>\n:* Between 392,979 and 942,636 estimated Iraqi (655,000 with a confidence interval of 95%), civilian and combatant, according to the second [[Lancet surveys of mortality before and after the 2003 invasion of Iraq|Lancet survey of mortality]].\n:* A minimum of 62,570 civilian deaths reported in the mass media up to 28 April 2007 according to [[Iraq Body Count project]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.IraqBodyCount.org |title=IraqBodyCount |publisher=IraqBodyCount |accessdate=26 March 2011}}</ref>\n:* 4,409 U.S. military dead (929 non-hostile deaths), and 31,926 wounded in action during Operation Iraqi Freedom.<ref name=\"Casualty Data USDOD\" /> 66 U.S. Military Dead (28 non-hostile deaths), and 295 wounded in action during Operation New Dawn.<ref name=\"Casualty Data USDOD\">{{cite web|url=http://www.defense.gov/NEWS/casualty.pdf |title=OPERATION IRAQI FREEDOM (OIF) U.S. CASUALTY STATUS * |author= |date=18 January 2013 |website=American Forces Press Service |publisher=United States Department of Defense |accessdate=19 January 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130116062321/http://www.defense.gov/news/casualty.pdf |archivedate=16 January 2013}}</ref>\n* Afghanistan: between 10,960 and 249,000<ref name=\"Casualties\" />\n{{Main|Civilian casualties of the War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)}}\n:* 16,725\u201319,013 civilians killed according to [[American Friends Service Committee#Cost of War project|Cost of War project]] from 2001 to 2013<ref>{{cite web |url=http://costsofwar.org/article/afghan-civilians |title=Afghan Civilians |publisher=Costs of War |date=27 February 2001 |accessdate=17 July 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130616010655/http://costsofwar.org/article/afghan-civilians |archivedate=16 June 2013}}</ref>\n:* According to Marc W. Herold's extensive database,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pubpages.unh.edu/~mwherold/dossier |title=Dossier on Civilian Victims of United States' Aerial Bombing |publisher=Pubpages.unh.edu |accessdate=26 March 2011}}</ref> between 3,100 and 3,600 civilians were directly killed by U.S. [[Operation Enduring Freedom]] bombing and Special Forces attacks between 7 October 2001 and 3 June 2003. This estimate counts only \"impact deaths\"\u2014deaths that occurred in the immediate aftermath of an explosion or shooting\u2014and does not count deaths that occurred later as a result of injuries sustained, or deaths that occurred as an indirect consequence of the U.S. airstrikes and invasion.\n:* In an opinion article published in August 2002 in the magazine ''[[The Weekly Standard]]'', [[Joshua Muravchik]] of the [[American Enterprise Institute]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://foreignpolicy.com/articles/2006/10/10/the_fp_memo_operation_comeback |title=The FP Memo: Operation Comeback \u2013 By Joshua Muravchik |publisher=Foreign Policy |date=10 October 2006 |accessdate=26 March 2011}}</ref> questioned Professor Herold's study entirely by one single incident that involved 25\u201393 deaths. He did not provide any estimate his own.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.weeklystandard.com/Content/Public/Articles/000/000/001/565otmps.asp?pg=1 |title=The Prof Who Can't Count Straight |publisher=The Weekly Standard |date=26 August 2002 |accessdate=26 March 2011}}</ref>\n:* In a pair of January 2002 studies, Carl Conetta of the Project on Defense Alternatives estimates that \"at least\" 4,200\u20134,500 civilians were killed by mid-January 2002 as a result of the war and Coalition airstrikes, both directly as casualties of the aerial bombing campaign, and indirectly in the resulting humanitarian crisis.\n:* His first study, \"Operation Enduring Freedom: Why a Higher Rate of Civilian Bombing Casualties?\",<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.comw.org/pda/0201oef.html |title=Operation Enduring Freedom: Why a Higher Rate of Civilian Bombing Casualties? |publisher=Comw.org |accessdate=26 March 2011}}</ref> released 18 January 2002, estimates that, at the low end, \"at least\" 1,000\u20131,300 civilians were directly killed in the aerial bombing campaign in just the three months between 7 October 2001 to 1 January 2002. The author found it impossible to provide an upper-end estimate to direct civilian casualties from the [[Operation Enduring Freedom]] bombing campaign that he noted as having an increased use of [[cluster bombs]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.comw.org/pda/0201oef.html#1 |title=Operation Enduring Freedom: Why a Higher Rate of Civilian Bombing Casualties \u2013 Bombers and cluster bombs |publisher=Comw.org |accessdate=26 March 2011}}</ref> In this lower-end estimate, only Western press sources were used for hard numbers, while heavy \"reduction factors\" were applied to Afghan government reports so that their estimates were reduced by as much as 75%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.comw.org/pda/0201oef.html#appendix1 |title=Operation Enduring Freedom: Why a Higher Rate of Civilian Bombing Casualties \u2013 Appendix 1. Estimation of Civilian Bombing Casualties: Method and Sources |publisher=Comw.org |accessdate=26 March 2011}}</ref>\n:* In his companion study, \"Strange Victory: A critical appraisal of Operation Enduring Freedom and the Afghanistan war\",<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.comw.org/pda/0201strangevic.html |title=Strange Victory: A critical appraisal of Operation Enduring Freedom and the Afghanistan war |publisher=Comw.org |accessdate=26 March 2011}}</ref> released 30 January 2002, Conetta estimates that \"at least\" 3,200 more Afghans died by mid-January 2002, of \"starvation, exposure, associated illnesses, or injury sustained while in flight from war zones\", as a result of the war and Coalition airstrikes.\n:* In similar numbers, a [[Los Angeles Times]] review of U.S., British, and Pakistani newspapers and international wire services found that between 1,067 and 1,201 direct civilian deaths were reported by those news organizations during the five months from 7 October 2001 to 28 February 2002. This review excluded all civilian deaths in Afghanistan that did not get reported by U.S., British, or Pakistani news, excluded 497 deaths that did get reported in U.S., British, and Pakistani news but that were not specifically identified as civilian or military, and excluded 754 civilian deaths that were reported by the Taliban but not independently confirmed.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.latimes.com/templates/misc/printstory.jsp?slug=la-060202bombs |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20020604082553/http://www.latimes.com/templates/misc/printstory.jsp?slug=la-060202bombs |archivedate=4 June 2002 |title=The Americans . . . They Just Drop Their Bombs and Leave |work=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=26 March 2011}}</ref>\n:* According to [[Jonathan Steele]] of ''[[The Guardian]]'' between 20,000 and 49,600 people may have died of the consequences of the invasion by the spring of 2002.<ref>\"[https://www.theguardian.com/world/2002/may/20/afghanistan.comment Forgotton Victims]\" ''The Guardian''</ref>\n:* 2,046 U.S. military dead (339 non-hostile deaths), and 18,201 wounded in action.<ref name=\"Casualty Data USDOD\" />\n:* A report titled ''Body Count'' put together by [[Physicians for Social Responsibility]], [[Physicians for Global Survival]], and [[International Physicians for the Prevention of Nuclear War]] (IPPNW) concluded that between 185,000\u2013249,000 people had been killed as a result of the fighting in Afghanistan.<ref name=\"Casualties\">\"[http://www.ippnw.de/commonFiles/pdfs/Frieden/Body_Count_first_international_edition_2015_final.pdf Body Count \u2013 Casualty Figures after 10 Years of the \"War on Terror\" \u2013 Iraq Afghanistan Pakistan]\" (PDF), by [[International Physicians for the Prevention of Nuclear War|IPPNW]], [[Physicians for Global Survival|PGS]] and [[Physicians for Social Responsibility|PSR]], p. 78, First international edition (March 2015)<br />{{cite news |author=Gabriela Motroc |url=http://www.australiannationalreview.com/war-terror-reportedly-killed-13-million-people-decade/ |title=U.S. War on Terror has reportedly killed 1.3 million people in a decade |work=Australian National Review |date=7 April 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150505004045/http://www.australiannationalreview.com/war-terror-reportedly-killed-13-million-people-decade/ |archivedate=5 May 2015}}<br />{{cite news |url=http://www.dailytimes.com.pk/national/30-Mar-2015/220-000-killed-in-us-war-in-afghanistan-80-000-in-pakistan-report |title=220,000 killed in US war in Afghanistan 80,000 in Pakistan: report |work=[[Daily Times (Pakistan)|Daily Times]] |date=30 March 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150505055409/http://www.dailytimes.com.pk/national/30-Mar-2015/220-000-killed-in-us-war-in-afghanistan-80-000-in-pakistan-report |archivedate=5 May 2015}}</ref>\n* Pakistan: Between 1467 and 2334 people were killed in U.S. drone attacks as of 6 May 2011. Tens of thousands have been killed by terrorist attacks, millions displaced. {{Main|Drone attacks in Pakistan|Terrorism in Pakistan}}\n* Somalia: 7,000+\n:* In December 2007, The Elman Peace and Human Rights Organization said it had verified 6,500 civilian deaths, 8,516 people wounded, and {{nowrap|1.5 million}} displaced from homes in Mogadishu alone during the year 2007.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://nationalpost.com/story.html?id=208509 |archive-url=https://www.webarchive.org.uk/wayback/archive/20141021035711/http://www.nationalpost.com/story.html?id%3D40babe8f%2D84b5%2D46d7%2Da311%2D344494e03788 |url-status=dead |archive-date=21 October 2014 |title=Mogadishu violence kills 6,500 in past year: rights group |date=21 March 2008 |accessdate=2 January 2012}}</ref>\n* USA\n:* 1 June 2009, Pvt. William Andrew Long was shot and killed by [[2009 Little Rock recruiting office shooting|Abdulhakim Muhammad]], while outside a recruiting facility in Little Rock AR.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/nationworld/2009314190_apusrecruitersshotfuneral.html |work=Seattle Times |title=Funeral held for soldier killed in Ark. attack |date=8 June 2009 |first=Jon |last=Gambrell |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110811184555/http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/nationworld/2009314190_apusrecruitersshotfuneral.html |archivedate=11 August 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"Associated Press\">{{cite news |title=Recruitment Shooting Suspect Doesn't Think Killing Was Murder |url=http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,525584,00.html |newspaper=Fox News |agency=Associated Press |date=9 June 2009 |accessdate=20 September 2009}}</ref>\n:* On 5 November 2009, [[Nidal Malik Hasan]] shot and killed 13 people and wounded more than 30 others at [[2009 Fort Hood shooting|Fort Hood, Texas]].<ref name=\"cbn.com\">{{cite news |title=Bill would give Purple Heart to Fort Hood shooting victims |url=http://www.statesman.com/news/news/local/bill-would-give-purple-heart-to-fort-hood-shooting/nRnc3/ |newspaper=Austin Statesman |date=9 May 2012 |accessdate=29 March 2013 |quote=Thirteen people were killed and more than 30 wounded in the rampage.}}</ref>\n'''Total casualties in Iraq and Afghanistan'''\nThis table shows a comparison of total casualties between the two main theaters of the War on Terror - Iraq (since [[2003 invasion of Iraq|2003]]) and Afghanistan (since [[U.S. invasion of Afghanistan|2001]]) - up until October 2018, as conducted by [[Brown University]].<ref>https://taskandpurpose.com/afghanistan-iraq-death-toll</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" id=\"conflicts10000\"\n|-\n! \n! Iraq\n! Afghanistan\n|-\n| align=center | U.S. military deaths\n| 4,550\n| 2,401\n|-\n| align=center | U.S. contractor deaths\n|3,793\n|3,937\n|-\n| align=center | National military and police deaths\n|41,726\n|58,596\n|-\n| align=center | Allied troop deaths\n|323\n|1,141\n|-\n| align=center | Civilian deaths\n|182,272\u2014204,575\n|38,480\n|-\n| align=center | Opposition fighters deaths\n|34,806\u201439,881\n|42,100\n|-\n| align=center | Journalist and media worker deaths\n|245\n|54\n|-\n| align=center | Humanitarian and NGO worker deaths\n|62\n|409\n|-\n| align=center | '''Total deaths'''\n|267,792\u2014295,170\n|147,124\n|}\n\n'''Total American casualties from the War on Terror''' <br />(<small>this includes fighting throughout the [[Earth|world]]</small>):<ref>{{cite web |url=http://icasualties.org/Iraq/index.aspx |title=Operation Iraqi Freedom &#124; Iraq |publisher=iCasualties |date=28 May 2010 |accessdate=26 March 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110321080348/http://icasualties.org/Iraq/index.aspx |archivedate=21 March 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=http://edition.cnn.com/SPECIALS/2003/iraq/forces/pow.mia/index.html |publisher=CNN | title=Forces: U.S. & Coalition/POW/MIA}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://siadapp.dmdc.osd.mil/personnel/CASUALTY/castop.htm |title=Military Casualty Information |publisher=Siadapp.dmdc.osd.mil |accessdate=26 March 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110303054755/http://siadapp.dmdc.osd.mil/personnel/CASUALTY/castop.htm |archivedate=3 March 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://icasualties.org/OEF/ByYear.aspx |title=OEF &#124; Afghanistan &#124; Fatalities By Year |publisher=iCasualties |date=28 May 2010 |accessdate=26 March 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.icasualties.org/OEF/Nationality.aspx?hndQry=US |title=Operation Iraqi Freedom &#124; Iraq &#124; Fatalities By Nationality |publisher=iCasualties |date=28 May 2010 |accessdate=26 March 2011}}</ref>\n{| class=wikitable\n|- style=\"background:#ccc;\"\n! Military and civilian !! Casualties  \n|-\n| U.S. military killed||7,008<ref name=\"Casualty Data USDOD\" />\n|-\n| U.S. military [[wounded in action|wounded]]|| 50,422<ref name=\"Casualty Data USDOD\" />\n|-\n| U.S. DoD civilians killed||16<ref name=\"Casualty Data USDOD\" />\n|-\n| U.S. civilians killed (includes [[9/11]] and after)|| 3,000 +\n|-\n| U.S. civilians wounded/injured||6,000 +\n|-\n| Total Americans killed (military and civilian)|| '''10,008 +'''\n|-\n| Total Americans wounded/injured||'''56,422 +'''\n|}\nThe [[United States Department of Veterans Affairs]] has diagnosed more than 200,000 American veterans with [[PTSD]] since 2001.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Aikins |first1=Matthieu |last2=Koehler |first2=Chris |year=2013 |title=Mental Combat |journal=[[Popular Science]] |volume=282 |issue=3 |pages=40\u201345 |url=http://www.popsci.com/technology/article/2013-02/us-armys-ambitious-fight-against-ptsd |accessdate=15 February 2013}}</ref>\n* Yemen\n{{Main|Terrorism in Yemen}}\n===Total terrorist casualties===\nThe total number of terrorist/insurgent/militant deaths since the commencement of the War on Terror in 2001 is generally estimated as being well into the hundreds of thousands, with hundreds of thousands of others captured or arrested.\n'''Iraq:'''\nIn Iraq, some 26,544 insurgents were killed by the American-led coalition and the Iraqi Security Forces from 2003 to 2011.<ref>597 killed in 2003,[https://www.usatoday.com/news/world/iraq/2007-09-26-insurgents_N.htm], 23,984 killed from 2004 through 2009 (with the exceptions of May 2004 and March 2009),[https://www.theguardian.com/world/2010/oct/22/true-civilian-body-count-iraq] 652 killed in May 2004,[http://www.iraqbodycount.org/analysis/numbers/warlogs/] 45 killed in March 2009,[http://www.reliefweb.int/rw/rwb.nsf/db900sid/CJAL-7QPQB7?OpenDocument] 676 killed in 2010,[https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-12-30/iraq-civilian-deaths-drop-for-third-year-as-toll-eases-after-u-s-drawdown.html] and 590 killed in 2011,[https://docs.google.com/spreadsheet/ccc?key=0Aia6y6NymliRdEZESktBSWVqNWM1dkZOSGNIVmtFZEE#gid=4] thus giving a total of 26,544 dead</ref> 119,752 suspected insurgents were arrested in Iraq from 2003 to 2007 alone, at which point 18,832 suspected insurgents had been reported killed;<ref>[https://www.stripes.com/news/insurgent-body-count-records-released-1.69423 \"Insurgent body count documents released.\"] Stars and Stripes. 1 October 2007. Number of convictions not specified.</ref> applying this same arrested-to-captured ratio to the total number of insurgents killed would equate to approximately 26,500 insurgents killed and 168,000 arrested from 2003 to 2011. At least 4,000 foreign fighters ([[Iraqi insurgency (2003-2011)#Foreign participants|generally estimated at 10-20% of the insurgency]] at that point) had been killed by September 2006, according to an official statement from [[Al-Qaeda in Iraq]].<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/world/2006/sep/28/iraq \"4,000 fighters killed, 'al-Qaida in Iraq' tape says.\"] The Guardian. September 28, 2006.</ref> Insurgent casualties in the [[Iraqi insurgency (2011\u20132013)|2011-2013 phase]] of the Iraqi conflict numbered 916 killed, with 3,504 more arrested.\n\nFrom 2014 to the end of 2017, the United States government stated that over 80,000 Islamic State insurgents had been killed by American and allied airstrikes from 2014 to the end of 2017, in both Iraq and Syria. The majority of these strikes occurred within Iraq.<ref>[https://www.straitstimes.com/world/middle-east/once-promised-paradise-isis-fighters-end-up-in-mass-graves \"Once promised paradise, ISIS fighters end up in mass graves\".] The Straits Times. 15 October 2017. Retrieved 11 December 2017.</ref> ISIS deaths caused by the Iraqi Security Forces in this time are uncertain, but were probably significant. Over 26,000 ISF members were killed fighting ISIS from 2013 to the end of 2017,<ref>[https://www.almasdarnews.com/article/26000-iraqi-soldiers-killed-4-year-war-isis/ \"Over 26,000 Iraqi soldiers killed in 4 year war with ISIS.\"] 13 December 2017.</ref> with ISIS losses likely being of a similar scale.\n\n'''Syria'''\nAccording to the [[Syrian Observatory for Human Rights]], 65,726 \"jihadi\" militants of non-Syrian nationalities were killed in Syria from 2011 up to March 2019, including members of [[Hayat Tahrir al-Sham]] (Al-Qaeda's Syria franchise), the Islamic State, the [[Turkistan Islamic Party]], and others. Many more \"jihadis\" of Syrian nationality were also killed, and not included in that total.<ref>[http://www.syriahr.com/en/?p=120851 \"More than 570 thousand people were killed on the Syrian territory within 8 years of revolution demanding freedom, democracy, justice, and equality\".] 15 March 2019.</ref> The SOHR also reported that American and other [[Combined Joint Task Force \u2013 Operation Inherent Resolve|CJTF-OIR]] airstrikes had killed a minimum of 9,156 ISIS fighters and 371 Al-Qaeda members in Syria up to July 2019,<ref>[http://www.syriahr.com/en/?p=135651 \"The 58th month since the start of the International Coalition\u2019s participation in military operations in Syria also goes without casualties among civilians, as security campaigns against ISIS cells intensify in east Euphrates area\".] SOHR. 23 July 2019. Retrieved 2 September 2019.</ref><ref>[http://www.syriahr.com/en/?p=139287 More casualties raise to at least 51, the death toll of Jihadis commanders and fighters killed in strikes of the International Coalition on their camp in Idlib countryside.]</ref> while Russian airstrikes had killed 5,260 ISIS fighters and 5,260 other militants (including members of both Islamist and non-Islamist rebel factions) up to July 2019.<ref>[http://www.syriahr.com/en/?p=136062 \"46 months of Russian military operations on the Syrian territory kill through its warplanes about 18715 people including 8208 civilians including about 1985 children\".] SOHR. 31 July 2019. Retrieved 30 May 2019.</ref> The American-backed [[Syrian Democratic Forces]] claimed to have killed 28,600+ ISIS members and captured 11,400+ up to March 2019.<ref>See [[Syrian Kurdish\u2013Islamist conflict (2013\u2013present)]] and [[Deir ez-Zor campaign (2017\u201319)]].</ref>\n\n'''Afghanistan'''\nInsurgent and terrorist deaths in Afghanistan are hard to estimate. [[Afghan Taliban]] losses are most likely of a similar scale to Afghan National Army and Police losses; that is around 62,000 from 2001 to the end of 2018.<ref>Rod Nordland; Mujib Mashal (26 January 2019). [https://www.nytimes.com/2019/01/26/world/asia/afghanistan-taliban-peace-deal.html \"U.S. and Taliban Edge Toward Deal to End America's Longest War\".] The New York Times. Retrieved 28 January 2019.</ref> In addition, Al-Qaeda's main branch and ISIS's Afghanistan branch are each thought to have lost several thousand killed there since 2001.<ref>\"In Afghanistan, al-Qaeda is working more closely with the Taliban, Pentagon says\". the Washington post. 6 May 2016.</ref><ref>Seldin, Jeff (18 November 2017). [https://www.voanews.com/east-asia-pacific/afghan-officials-islamic-state-fighters-finding-sanctuary-afghanistan \"Afghan Officials: Islamic State Fighters Finding Sanctuary in Afghanistan\".] VOA News. ISSN 0261-3077. Retrieved 18 November 2017.</ref>\n\n'''Pakistan'''\nThe [[War in Northwest Pakistan]] resulted in the deaths of 28,900+ militants from 2004 to 2018, with an unknown number captured, per the Pakistani government.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://satp.org/datasheet-terrorist-attack/fatalities/pakistan-khyberpakhtunkhwa|title=Database \u2013 KPK from 2005 to present|publisher=|accessdate=24 May 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://satp.org/datasheet-terrorist-attack/fatalities/pakistan-fata|title=Database \u2013 FATA from 2005 to present|publisher=|accessdate=24 May 2019}}</ref> The majority of these were killed in engagements with the [[Pakistan Armed Forces]]. However, thousands were also killed in American [[Drone strikes in Pakistan|drone strikes]].\n\n'''Other theaters'''\nAmerican forces (mostly via drone strikes) killed between 846 and 1,609 terrorists in Yemen (mostly [[Al-Qaeda in the Arabian Peninsula|AQAP]] members) up to June 2019, according to a variety of media organizations including the Bureau of Investigative Journalism and the New America Foundation.<ref>See [[List of drone strikes in Yemen]].</ref> An [[United Arab Emirates|Emirati]] spokesman for the [[Saudi Arabian-led intervention in Yemen|Saudi-led coalition intervening in Yemen]] claimed that they had killed 1,000 Al-Qaeda linked militants and captured 1,500 up to August 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1426857|title=UAE aims to wipe out Yemen Al Qaeda branch|work=Dawn|accessdate=14 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe December 2006 to January 2009 [[Somali Civil War (2006\u20132009)|Ethiopian-led intervention]] in [[Somalia]] resulted in the deaths of 6,000 to 8,000 Islamist insurgents, according to the Ethiopian government.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://sudantribune.com/spip.php?article19495 |title=Ethiopian army accomplished 75% of mission in Somalia \u2013 Zenawi |publisher=SudanTribune article |accessdate=2011-07-09 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070102124635/http://www.sudantribune.com/spip.php?article19495 |archive-date=January 2, 2007 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | first =David | last =Ignatius | title =Ethiopia's Iraq | work =Washington Post | date =May 13, 2007 | url =https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/05/11/AR2007051102114.html | accessdate =2007-05-16 | archive-url =https://web.archive.org/web/20171014001910/http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/05/11/AR2007051102114.html | archive-date =October 14, 2017 | url-status=live | df =mdy-all}}</ref> The Kenyan Defence Forces claimed another 700+ insurgents killed in their own intervention of October 2011 to May 2012.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://mobile.nation.co.ke/News/KDF+We+have+killed+700+militants+/-/1290/1301746/-/format/xhtml/-/dvc8mh/-/index.html|archive-url=https://archive.today/20130111204256/http://mobile.nation.co.ke/News/KDF+We+have+killed+700+militants+/-/1290/1301746/-/format/xhtml/-/dvc8mh/-/index.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=11 January 2013|work=[[Daily Nation]]|title=KDF: We have killed 700 militants|date=7 January 2012|accessdate=7 January 2012}}</ref> American drone strikes, air strikes, and special forces ground raids in Somalia killed between 1,220 and 1,366 militants up to July 2019, according to the New American Foundation.<ref>[https://www.newamerica.org/in-depth/americas-counterterrorism-wars/somalia/ U.S. Air Strikes, Drone Strikes, and Ground Raids in Somalia.] New America Foundation. Retrieved August 19, 2019.</ref>\n\nOver 1,600 Islamic State fighters ([[Abu Sayyaf]] having sworn allegiance to ISIS in 2014) were killed by government forces in the Philippines from 2014 to 2017 alone.<ref>See [[Civil conflict in the Philippines#Casualties by year|civil conflict in the Philippines.]]</ref>\n\nFrom April 2009 to March 2019, Russian military and police (primarily in the [[North Caucasus]]) killed 2,329 and captured 2,744 insurgents of the [[Caucasus Emirate]] and related groups.<ref>270 killed and 453 captured (2009),[http://chechnya.kavkaz-uzel.ru/articles/159998] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110920151411/http://chechnya.kavkaz-uzel.ru/articles/159998 |date=20 September 2011}} 349 killed and 254 captured (2010),[http://www.kavkaz-uzel.ru/articles/198756] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120419012428/http://www.kavkaz-uzel.ru/articles/198756/ |date=19 April 2012}} 384 killed and 370 captured (2011),[http://www.kavkaz-uzel.ru/articles/198756/]  391 killed and 461 captured (2012),[http://de.sputniknews.com/politik/20130125/265394634.html] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150122191400/http://de.sputniknews.com/politik/20130125/265394634.html |date=22 January 2015}} 260 killed (2013),[http://sputniknews.com/russia/20131224/185892322.html] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150122191323/http://sputniknews.com/russia/20131224/185892322.html |date=22 January 2015}} and 88 captured [http://sputniknews.com/russia/20130502/180951073/North-Caucasus-Militants-Losses-Down-in-2013.html] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150122190947/http://sputniknews.com/russia/20130502/180951073/North-Caucasus-Militants-Losses-Down-in-2013.html |date=22 January 2015}} 259 killed and 445 captured (2014),[https://web.archive.org/web/20150203055846/http://www.jamestown.org/programs/edm/single/?tx_ttnews%5Btt_news%5D=43475&cHash=37f7f6ab5a72bfb5b02b545a639f5fc4] 172 killed (2015),[http://www.kavkaz-uzel.eu/articles/277116/] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170617101542/http://www.kavkaz-uzel.eu/articles/277116 |date=17 June 2017}} 162 killed and 377 captured (2016),[http://www.kavkaz-uzel.eu/articles/297004/] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170204172900/http://www.kavkaz-uzel.eu/articles/297004 |date=4 February 2017}}[https://sputniknews.com/russia/201610111046220627-russia-north-caucasus-militants/] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170916160321/https://sputniknews.com/russia/201610111046220627-russia-north-caucasus-militants/ |date=16 September 2017}} 82 killed and 296 captured (2017),[https://www.kavkaz-uzel.eu/articles/315790/] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190327191044/https://www.kavkaz-uzel.eu/articles/315790/ |date=27 March 2019}}[https://www.rferl.org/a/caucasus-report-jump-in-militant-arrests/28831632.html] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190327192355/https://www.rferl.org/a/caucasus-report-jump-in-militant-arrests/28831632.html |date=27 March 2019}} total reported 2,329 killed and 2,744 captured</ref>\n\n==Costs==\nThe War on Terror, spanning decades, is a multitrillion-dollar war.\n\nAccording to the Costs of War Project at [[Watson Institute for International and Public Affairs|Brown University's Watson Institute]], the War on Terror will have cost $5.6 trillion for operations between 2001-2018 plus anticipated future costs of veterans' care.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Engelhardt|first1=Tom|title=America's 'War on Terror' Has Cost Taxpayers $5.6 Trillion|url=https://www.thenation.com/article/americas-war-on-terror-has-cost-taxpayers-5-6-trillion/|accessdate=20 May 2018|work=The Nation|date=18 May 2018}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the Soufan Group in July 2015, the U.S. government was spending {{nowrap|$9.4 million}} per day in operations against ISIS in Syria and Iraq.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://soufangroup.com/tsg-intelbrief-terrorism-in-the-horn-of-africa/|title=TSG IntelBrief: Terrorism in the Horn of Africa|date=28 July 2015|accessdate=28 July 2015|publisher=The Soufan Group |location=New York, NY}}</ref>\n\nA March 2011 Congressional report<ref name=\"Daniel Trotta\">{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2011/06/29/us-usa-war-idUSTRE75S25320110629|title=Cost of war at least $3.7 trillion and counting|author=Daniel Trotta|agency=[[Reuters]]|date=29 June 2011|accessdate=25 June 2012}}</ref> estimated war spending through the fiscal year 2011 at $1.2 trillion, and future spending through 2021 (assuming a reduction to 45,000 troops) at $1.8 trillion. A June 2011 academic report<ref name=\"Daniel Trotta\" /> covering additional areas of war spending estimated it through 2011 at $2.7 trillion, and long-term spending at $5.4 trillion including interest.<ref group=\"note\">Among costs not covered by these figures are off-[[United States Department of Defense|DoD]] spending beyond 2012, economic opportunity costs, state and local expenses not reimbursed by the federal government, nor reimbursements made to foreign coalition allies for their expenses.</ref>\n\nIn direct costs, the [[United States Department of Defense]] reports spending $1.5 trillion from 2001 to March 2019 in war costs in Iraq, Syria, and Afghanistan.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://comptroller.defense.gov/Portals/45/documents/Section1090Reports/Section_1090_FY17_NDAA_Cost_of_Wars_to_Per_Taxpayer-March_2019.pdf|title=Estimated Cost to Each U.S. Taxpayer of Each of the Wars in Afghanistan, Iraq and Syria - March 2019|last=|first=|date=|website=Under Secretary of Defense (Comptroller)|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=23 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Expense !! [[Congressional Research Service|CRS]]/[[Congressional Budget Office|CBO]] (billions US$):<ref>{{cite web|url=https://opencrs.com/document/RL33110/2010-07-16/ |title=The Cost of Iraq, Afghanistan, and Other Global War on Terror Operations Since 2011 |author=Amy Belasco |publisher=[[Congressional Research Service]] |date=16 July 2010 |accessdate=25 June 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110127150911/http://opencrs.com/document/RL33110/2010-07-16/ |archivedate=27 January 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://opencrs.com/document/RL33498/ |title=Pakistan-U.S. Relations |author=K. Alan Kronstadt |publisher=[[Congressional Research Service]] |date=6 February 2009 |accessdate=25 June 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111222151047/http://opencrs.com/document/RL33498/ |archivedate=22 December 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n|url=http://cbo.gov/publication/21982|title=Long-Term Implications of the 2011 Future Years Defense Program|author=Congressional Research Service|date=11 February 2011|accessdate=25 June 2012|author-link=Congressional Research Service}}</ref> !! '''[[Watson Institute for International Studies|Watson]] (billions [[Constant dollars|constant]] US$):'''<ref>{{cite web |url=http://costsofwar.org/article/economic-cost-summary |title=Cost of Iraq, Afghanistan, and Anti-Terrorism Operations |author=Eisenhower Study Group |publisher=[[Watson Institute for International Studies]], [[Brown University]] |year=2011 |accessdate=24 June 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120628171525/http://costsofwar.org/article/economic-cost-summary |archivedate=28 June 2012}}</ref>\n|-\n|colspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align: center;\" | '''FY2001\u2013FY2011'''\n|-\n|War appropriations to [[United States Department of Defense|DoD]]||1208.1|| 1311.5\n|-\n|War appropriations to [[United States Department of State|DoS]]/[[United States Agency for International Development|USAID]]|| 66.7 || 74.2\n|-\n|[[United States Department of Veterans Affairs|VA]] Medical|| 8.4 || 13.7\n|-\n|VA disability||   || 18.9\n|-\n|Interest paid on DoD war appropriations||   || 185.4\n|-\n|Additions to DoD base spending ||   || 362.2\u2013652.4\n|-\n|Additions to Homeland Security base spending ||   || 401.2\n|-\n|Social costs to veterans and military families to date ||   || 295\u2013400\n|-\n|'''Subtotal:''' || '''1,283.2''' || '''2,662.1\u20133,057.3'''\n|-\n|colspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align: center;\" | '''FY2012\u2013future'''\n|-\n|FY2012 DoD request || colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align: center;\" | 118.4\n|-\n|FY2012 DoS/USAID request || colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align: center;\" | 12.1\n|-\n|Projected 2013\u20132015 war spending || colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align: center;\" | 168.6\n|-\n|Projected 2016\u20132020 war spending || colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align: center;\" | 155\n|-\n|Projected obligations for veterans' care to 2051 ||   || 589\u2013934\n|-\n|Additional interest payments to 2020 ||   || 1,000\n|-\n|'''Subtotal:''' || '''454.1''' || '''2043.1\u20132388.1'''\n|-\n|'''Total:''' || '''1737.3''' || '''4705.2\u20135445.4'''\n|}\n\n==Criticism==\n{{Main|Criticism of the War on Terror}}\n{{See also|United States war crimes}}\n[[File:World Can't Wait J4 Demo.jpg|thumb|Participants in a rally, dressed as hooded detainees]]\nCriticism of the War on Terror addressed the issues, morality, efficiency, economics, and other questions surrounding the War on Terror and made against the phrase itself, calling it a [[misnomer]]. The notion of a \"war\" against \"terrorism\" has proven highly contentious, with critics charging that it has been exploited by participating governments to pursue long-standing policy/military objectives,<ref name=\"Monbiot2003\">[[George Monbiot]], [http://www.monbiot.com/archives/2003/03/11/a-wilful-blindness \"A Wilful Blindness\"] (\"Those who support the coming war with Iraq refuse to see that it has anything to do with US global domination\"), ''monbiot.com'' (author's website archives), reposted from ''[[The Guardian]]'', 11 March 2003. Retrieved 28 May 2007.</ref> reduce [[civil liberties]],<ref name=\"Wired-FBI\">{{cite news|url=https://www.wired.com/threatlevel/2008/03/fbi-tried-to-co/|title=FBI Tried to Cover Patriot Act Abuses With Flawed, Retroactive Subpoenas, Audit Finds|last=Singel|first=Ryan|date=13 March 2008|work=Wired |accessdate=13 February 2012}}</ref> and infringe upon human rights. It is argued that the term war is not appropriate in this context (as in [[War on Drugs]]) since there is no identifiable enemy and that it is unlikely international terrorism can be brought to an end by military means.<ref name=\"Richissin\">{{cite news|url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/nationworld/2002023596_russanal02.html |title=\"War on terror\" difficult to define |last=Richissin |first=Todd |date=2 September 2004 |work=The Baltimore Sun |accessdate=28 January 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090114085106/http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/nationworld/2002023596_russanal02.html |archivedate=14 January 2009}}</ref>\n\nOther critics, such as [[Francis Fukuyama]], note that \"[[Definition of terrorism|terrorism]]\" is not an enemy, but a tactic; calling it a \"war on terror\", obscures differences between conflicts such as anti-occupation [[Insurgency|insurgents]] and international [[mujahideen]]. With a military presence in [[Iraq]] and [[Afghanistan]] and its associated collateral damage, [[Shirley Williams]] maintains this increases resentment and terrorist threats against the West.<ref>Williams, Shirley. \"[https://www.theguardian.com/comment/story/0,3604,1072390,00.html The seeds of Iraq's future terror]\". ''[[The Guardian]]'', 28 October 2003.</ref> There is also perceived U.S. hypocrisy,<ref name=\"odom_terrorismtactic\">{{cite web|url=http://www.middlebury.edu/media/view/214721/original/OdomPaper.pdf |title=American Hegemony: How to Use It, How to Lose It by Gen. William Odom |accessdate=27 February 2014}}</ref><ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2009/06/03/opinion/03iht-edalbright.html?_r=1 Obama's Muslim Speech], ''[[The New York Times]]'', by [[Madeleine Albright]], retrieved on 25 April 2016 \"According to Muslim speakers at such events, one fact stands out: When the cold war ended, America needed an enemy to replace Communism and chose Islam...Mr. Obama's dilemma is that no speech, however eloquent, can disentangle U.S.-Muslim relations from the treacherous terrain of current events in places such as Iraq, Afghanistan, Pakistan, Iran and the Middle East...Muslims desire respect and respect demands frankness. We cannot pretend that American soldiers and aircraft are not attacking Muslims.\" Archived from the [https://web.archive.org/web/20160719111308/http://www.nytimes.com/2009/06/03/opinion/03iht-edalbright.html?_r=1 original]</ref> media-induced hysteria,<ref>{{cite book|last=Lustick|first=Ian S.|title=Trapped in the War on Terror|publisher=University of Pennsylvania Press|isbn=978-0-8122-3983-6|year=2006|origyear=1 September 2006|url=https://archive.org/details/trappedinwaronte00lust}}</ref> and that differences in foreign and security policy have [[Criticism of United States foreign policy|damaged America's reputation internationally]].<ref name=\"PEW-2007\">{{cite web|url=http://www.pewglobal.org/2007/03/14/americas-image-in-the-world-findings-from-the-pew-global-attitudes-project/|title=America's Image in the World: Findings from the Pew Global Attitudes Project |date=14 March 2007 |publisher=Pew Research Center|accessdate=13 February 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Other Wars on Terror==\nIn the 2010s, [[People's Republic of China|China]] has also been engaged in its own War on Terror, predominantly a domestic campaign in response to violent actions by [[Uyghur people|Uyghur]] separatist movements in the [[Xinjiang conflict]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cfr.org/china/chinas-war-terror-september-11-uighur-separatism/p4765|title=China's 'War on Terror': September 11 and Uighur Separatism|date=|publisher=Council on Foreign Relations|accessdate=10 September 2015}}</ref> This campaign was widely criticized in international media due to the perception that it unfairly targets and [[persecutes]] [[Chinese Muslims]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/chinas-war-on-terror-becomes-all-out-attack-on-islam-in-xinjiang/2014/09/19/5c5840a4-1aa7-4bb6-bc63-69f6bfba07e9_story.html|title=China's war on terror becomes all-out attack on Islam in Xinjiang|author=Simon Denyer|date=19 September 2014|website=Washington Post|accessdate=10 September 2015}}</ref> potentially resulting in a negative backlash from [[China]]'s predominantly [[Muslim]] [[Uyghur people|Uighur]] population. [[Xi Jinping]]'s government has imprisoned up to 2 million [[Uyghurs]] and other [[Islam in China|Muslim]] ethnic minorities in [[Xinjiang re-education camps]], where they are reportedly subject to abuse and torture.<ref>{{cite news |title=Saudi crown prince defended China's imprisonment of a million Muslims in internment camps, giving Xi Jinping a reason to continue his 'precursors to genocide' |url=https://www.businessinsider.com/saudi-crown-prince-defends-china-oppression-of-muslims-in-xinjiang-mohammed-bin-salman-2019-2 |work=Business Insider |date=23 February 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Saudi crown prince defends China's right to fight 'terrorism' |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2019/02/saudi-crown-prince-defends-china-fight-terrorism-190223104647149.html |work=al-Jazeera |date=23 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n[[Russia]] has also been engaged on its own, also largely internally focused, counter-terrorism campaign often termed a war on terror, during the [[Second Chechen War]], the [[Insurgency in the North Caucasus]], and the [[Russian military intervention in the Syrian Civil War]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://content.time.com/time/world/article/0,8599,2093529,00.html |work=Time |title=How the War on Terrorism Did Russia a Favor |date=19 September 2011}}</ref> Like [[China]]'s war on terror, [[Russia]] has also been focused on [[separatist]] and [[Islamist]] movements that use [[political violence]] to achieve their ends.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gwu.edu/~ieresgwu/assets/docs/demokratizatsiya%20archive/10-4_Cohen.PDF |title=Russia, Islam, and the War on Terrorism |first=Ariel |last=Cohen |accessdate=29 November 2015}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Islam|United States|Politics}}\n{{div col|colwidth=14em}}\n* [[AfPak]]\n* [[Appeal to fear]]\n* [[Attacks on U.S. consulate in Karachi]]\n* [[Axis of evil]]\n* [[Bush Doctrine]]\n* [[Cold War]]\n* [[Culture of fear]]\n* [[Foreign policy of the United States]]\n* [[Iran and state-sponsored terrorism]]\n* [[Islamic terrorism in Europe (2014\u2013present)]]\n* [[List of military operations in the War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)]]\n* [[Nuclear terrorism]]\n* [[Pakistan\u2013United States relations]]\n* [[Protecting the Nation from Foreign Terrorist Entry into the United States (disambiguation)|Protecting the Nation from Foreign Terrorist Entry into the United States]]\n* [[State Sponsors of Terrorism]]\n* [[Targeted killing]]\n* [[Timeline of the War on Terror]]\n* [[Timeline of United States military operations]]\n* [[List of wars involving the United States|History of the United States at War]]\n* [[United States and state terrorism]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|group=note}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Sergei Boeke, [https://web.archive.org/web/20141021143302/http://www.icct.nl/publications/icct-papers/transitioning-from-military-interventions-to-a-long-term-counter-terrorism-policy ''Transitioning from Military Interventions to a Long-Term Counter-Terrorism Policy'' (International Centre for Counter-Terrorism \u2013 The Hague, 2014)]\n* {{Cite book\n|last = Coughlin\n|first = Stephen\n|year = 2015\n|title = Catastrophic Failure: Blindfolding America in the Face of Jihad\n|publisher = CreateSpace Independent Publishing Platform\n|isbn = 978-1511617505\n}}\n* Jackson, Richard. ''Writing the War on Terrorism: Language, Politics and Counter-Terrorism''. Manchester & New York: Manchester University Press, 2005. {{ISBN|0719071216}}.\n\n==External links==\n\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* [https://georgewbush-whitehouse.archives.gov/infocus/nationalsecurity/faq-what.html White House information about the War on Terrorism]\n* [https://www.cia.gov/news-information/cia-the-war-on-terrorism/index.html CIA and the War on Terrorism]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110806164227/http://www.defense.gov/qdr/docs/2005-01-25-Strategic-Plan.pdf U.S. National Military Strategic Plan for the War on Terrorism], 2006\n{{Navboxes|title=Art